<HEAD>Disgruntled Fast-Food Customer Speeds Off To Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Restores day of week to 1st graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man angered when his order was
misunderstood at a fast-food restaurant drive-up window sped away
Friday, lost control of his car, and died after it hit a utility
pole and flipped, police said.
   Vance F. Martin, 25, was pronounced dead at Ball Memorial
Hospital shortly after the 2:33 a.m. accident. An autopsy showed he
died of massive head injuries, said Delaware County Coroner Jack
Stonebraker Jr.
   Martin's car struck a concrete median, became airborne for 40
feet and hit a large rock and a pole before flipping once. He was
not wearing a seat belt and was thrown from the car, police said.
   An employee at the restaurant near the accident scene told
police Martin became upset after employees could not understand his
order. When he was asked to drive to the window and place the
order, Martin left the restaurant at a high rate of speed, police
said.
</TEXT>
