<HEAD>FAA Orders Inspection of Brakes on Long-Range DC-10s</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf in 1st item, Under the, to CORRECT that
inspection becomes effective Aug. 10, not ends on that date.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has
ordered a special inspection of landing gear brakes on long-range
McDonnell Douglas DC-10 aircraft.
   The agency also directed that the brakes be replaced if they
exceed prescribed wear limits.
   Friday's order came in response to a May 21 accident involving
an American Airlines DC-10 last May in which eight of the plane's
10 brakes failed when the pilot aborted his takeoff.
   In that incident the plane skidded 1,000 feet beyond the runway
at the Dallas-Fort Worth airport, the three cockpit crewmembers and
five of the 240 passengers were injured and the plane was heavily
damaged.
   The inspection order becomes effective Aug. 20, although
inspections may begin before that, said agency spokesman Dick
Stafford.
   The FAA directive applies only to McDonnell Douglas DC-10 Series
30 and Series 40 planes, the somewhat heavier long-range version of
the aircraft, said Stafford.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Fines Texas Currency Dealer $3.01 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department has announced it is
imposing the first civil penalty fines in its efforts to halt money
laundering along the border with Mexico.
   The department said Friday it is levied a $3.01 million fined on
Oscar's Money Exchange of Hidalgo, Texas, and its owner, Oscar
Ortiz Alvarez, and another man, Antonio Franco.
   Franco's organization was accused of violating the Bank Secrecy
Act by alledgedly laundering $5.56 million through Oscar's Money
Exchange. Federal agents in June 1987 seized $2.55 million. The
remaining $3.01 million was transported to Mexico by Alvarez and
others without filing the necessary forms with the U.S. Customs
Service, the department said.
   The Bank Secrecy Act requires anyone transporting cash of
$10,000 or more outside the country to notify the Customs Service.
   Alvarez, arrested in McAllen, Texas, on Thursday, was charged in
the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of Texas with
money laundering.
   The department said Franco is serving 35 years in a federal
prison after being convicted of participating in a drug smuggling
and distribution ring.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>GSA Pushes Back Deadline For New Federal Phone System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Services Administration says it
will wait until the end of the year to award bids for an all-new
federal telephone system known as FTS 2000.
   In a brief statement, the GSA said Friday the award of the
contracts, scheduled for Sept. 30, was delayed ``to make available
additional time for evaluating the large amount of technical and
financial bid data.''
   The contracts, worth as much as $25 billion over 10 years, were
originally scheduled to have been awarded by the end of 1987.
However, that date slipped when the GSA, under pressure from
Congress, decided to split the contract, with 60 percent going to
one vendor and 40 percent to another.
   US Sprint Communications Co., a team headed by American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. and another headed by Martin Marietta
Corp. with MCI Communications Corp. have placed bids for the
contract, one of the biggest ever let by the government.
   AT&T spokesman Herb Linnen said the company was ``very
disturbed'' by the delay.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Plans To Nominate Ambassador To Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House says President Reagan plans to
nominate James E. Goodby, a veteran Foreign Service officer as
ambassador to Greece.
   Goodby, 58, who entered the Foreign Service in 1952 is now a
diplomat in residence at the Foreign Service Institute. He will
succeed Robert Vossler Keeley on his confirmation by the Senate.
   Goodby was ambassador to Finland in 1980-81, vice chairman of
the U.S. delegation to the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks from
1981-83, and U.S. representative to the Conference on Security
Building Measures and Disarmament in Europe from 1983-85.
   He was diplomat in residence at Georgetown University in 1985-86
and since 1987 has been diplomat in residence and senior fellow for
the Center for the study of Foreign Affairs at the Foreign Service
Institute, the State Department's training agency.
</TEXT>
