<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Bomb 3rdLd-Writethru a0503 07-30 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Bomb, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0503,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Explosion At Shopping Plaza Injures 57</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throuout to UPDATE with more details on shopping center
bomb, device defused at theater, no comment from ANC. No pickup.
^By GREG MYRE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb ripped through a busy
shopping plaza today, injuring 57 people, seven of them critically,
police said.
   Elsewhere, a mine exploded at a bus stop, an explosive device
was defused at a theater and seven people were killed in scattered
violence.
   The incidents occurred one day after the government banned the
anti-apartheid film ``Cry Freedom'' after it was shown in theaters
nationwide.
   The bomb at the shopping plaza exploded just after noon in a
fast-food restaurant in Benoni, a white suburb 12 miles east of
Johannesburg, said police spokesman G.J. Everson.
   Police initially said one person was killed, but another
spokesman, Lt. Willem Meyer, said later that no deaths had been
confirmed. He said the seven people in critical condition had been
taken to Johannesburg Hospital.
   The Wimpy's hamburger restaurant and adjacent shops were badly
damaged, with windows shattered throughout the two-story plaza,
Meyer said. The plaza was packed with shoppers, most of them white,
witnesses said. However, some of those injured were black, the
witnesses added.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blast.
   Police have blamed virtualy all of more than 90 bombings in
South Africa during a 25-month state-of-emergency on the outlawed
African National Congress, the main black guerrilla group fighting
the white-led government. The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, seldom
confirms or denies involvement in the attacks.
   In a separate incident, a suspected limpet mine exploded today
at a bus stop in Germiston, 10 miles southeast of Johannesburg. It
slightly injured one person, police said. No one claimed
responsibility.
   Such mines can be attached to another surface.
   In Pretoria, the South African capital, police today discovered
an explosive device at a Metro theater complex, where ``Cry
Freedom'' was shown Friday. Police cordoned off the area and bomb
experts defused the device.
   It was discovered one day after police confiscated copies of the
film seven hours after it opened in more than 30 theaters
nationwide.
   The film, about black activist Steve Biko, had been approved by
censors but police said two explosions at theaters, bomb threats
and violent scenes in the movie proved it was a threat to public
safety.
   Elsewhere, seven blacks were killed in five separate attacks
over the past 24 hours in the Natal province and the Soweto
township outside Johannesburg, police said in their daily unrest
report.
   One black man was fatally stabbed and three seriously injured
when they were attacked by black students in Soweto, a police
statement said.
   In Natal, the site of ongoing factional fighting, three men were
stabbed to death when a group of blacks attacked a private home,
police said.
   In two other incidents, a group of blacks stabbed a woman to
death and a private vehicle was set on fire, killing the only
occupant, the report said.
   One additional man was stabbed to death in Natal in an attack on
a private home, the report said.
   The sketchy police unrest statement covers incidents reported
during the previous 24 hours, but gives few details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
