<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-HoseaWilliams     07-30 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Hosea Williams,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Warrant Issued For Hosea Williams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arrest warrant has been issued for City
Councilman and veteran civil rights activist Hosea Williams, who is
accused of trying to board an airplane with a handgun.
   Williams was indicted Thursday on a single count of possession
of a firearm by a convicted felon. The incident allegedly occurred
in March at Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport.
   ``We have been in contact with Mr. Williams and he has indicated
he will turn himself in,'' said Stanley Tuggle, chief of
administrative operations for the Clayton County Sheriff's
Department. Calls to Williams went unanswered Saturday.
   Police said they found a .38-caliber handgun and five bullets
inside Williams' briefcase when he was stopped March 6 at an
airport security checkpoint.
   Williams, 62, told police he had put the gun in his briefcase
while cleaning out his car and was allowed to board the plane after
the gun and ammunition were confiscated.
   At first he was charged only with misdemeanors, but the charges
were upgraded to a felony count after a review of Williams' record,
Tuggle said.
   In addition to arrests during the civil rights era, Williams has
a long history of traffic offenses. Police records show more than
25 convictions, guilty pleas and bond forfeitures over the past two
decades, including 180 days served in jail for leaving the scene of
an accident in 1980.
</TEXT>
