<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Arrests     07-30 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Arrests,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Czechoslovak Activists Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Czechoslovak activists were detained
in separate incidents for anti-government activities, including
supporting Soviet-style reforms and blaming the government for the
death of another activist, emigre sources said Saturday.
   The two could each face prison sentences of up to three years,
according to the Czechoslovak sources in Vienna, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   According to the sources, police detained Miroslav Polak on May
5 after he blamed police and the courts for the death in prison of
human rights activist Pavel Wonka. Wonka died in April.
   The sources, quoting a statement by the Committee in Defense of
the Unjustly Persecuted, said Polak made the remarks to a friend
while riding a streetcar.
   The sources said police forced the activist and his friend, who
was not identified, into a police car immediately after their
conversation.
   Polak, a member of the Charter 77 human rights group, was
released the next day. He was charged with swearing at and
physically attacking police while under the influence of alcohol,
the statement said.
   In a separate incident, Jaroslav Popelka, an activist from the
city of Brno, about 130 miles southeast of Prague, was arrested
April 14 after distributing leaflets calling on the Czechoslovak
government to implement Soviet-style reforms, the sources said,
quoting the statement.
   They said Popelka, 32, demanded the resignation of some
Czechoslovak leaders and called on citizens to demonstrate
peacefully for change.
   Police confiscated manuscripts and a typewriter during searches
of the apartments of Popelka and his brother, according to the
sources.
   They said Popelka was released from custody May 13 but was
detained again June 17, allegedly because he refused to cease his
activities. He was charged with disturbing the peace, the sources
said.
</TEXT>
