<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Arrests 3rdLd-Writethru a0506 07-30 0866</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Arrests, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0506,0885</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Government Arrests Leading Dissident, Other Critics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3 graf for 6-8 grafs pvs, ``In Washington...of
anonymity.'' to UPDATE with State Dept. saying 25 arrested,
including Aung Gyi and AP reporter. Pickup 9th graf pvs, ``In
a...'' TRIMs last graf pvs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Burmese government of hardliner
Sein Lwin arrested a major opposition figure, at least 10 other
critics and an Associated Press reporter, Western diplomats said
today.
   Aung Gyi, who once was considered a likely presidential
successor, was among those seized during a roundup of dissidents
late Friday and early today, said diplomats contacted in Rangoon,
the Burmese capital.
   The reported sweep took place one week after Burmese leader Ne
Win resigned as chairman of the ruling party and set in motion
changes which appear to have brought even more hard-line leaders
into power.
   Aung Gyi, 70, had written a series of letters sharply critical
of economic and political conditions in Burma, the site of recent
student unrest. Aung Gyi targeted Sein Lwin, new chairman of the
Burma Socialist Program Party, for criticism in connection with the
bloody suppression of the student protests.
   There has been no official announcement of the arrests, the
first known crackdown on dissidents since Sein Lwin assumed the
chairmanship on Tuesday.
   In Washington, Nancy Beck, a State Department spokeswoman, said
U.S. officials in Burma ``understand that perhaps as many as 25
people have been arrested,'' including Aung Gyi and Associated
Press correspondent Sein Win.
   She said U.S. officials have no other details on the arrests.
``We are making inquiries but are limited in what we can do by the
fact that Sein Win is a Burmese, not a U.S. citizen,'' she said.
   The Western diplomats, reached by telephone from Bangkok, said
Sein Win was taken from his home in the northern suburbs of Rangoon
by authorities at around midnight Friday. The diplomats spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   In a brief telex to the Associated Press bureau in Bangkok, Sein
Win's family said, ``Daddy has been taken away. He won't be be
available to answer your queries.'' The message was received
shortly after his arrest.
   The 66-year-old newsman, former publisher of the
English-language daily, The Guardian, was jailed for three years in
the 1960s in connection with his journalistic activities. In 1963
he was awarded the Golden Pen of Freedom by the Paris-based
International Federation of Journalists for his work in fostering a
free press in Burma.
   Aung Gyi, a onetime comrade-in-arms of Ne Win, sided with the
general when he staged a 1962 coup against the civilian government.
Aung Gyi served as vice chairman of the Revolutionary Council and
Minister for Trade Development and Industries.
   Regarded then as his probable successor, the pragmatic,
relatively liberal Aung Gyi fell out with Ne Win over plans to
nationalize the economy and resigned from his positions in 1963. He
was subsequently jailed.
   Recently he re-emerged in the public eye through a series of
critical letters unprecedented in the rigidly controlled country.
Although addressed to Ne Win and other Burmese leaders, the letters
were widely circulated in Rangoon and _ according to one Burmese
source _ ``sold like hotcakes.''
   Aung Gyi refrained from attacking Ne Win personally but sharply
criticized men around him and the general state of the country.
   ``That the country has gone from bad to worse (26) years after
the seizure of power is evident to anyone not living in a fool's
paradise...,'' he wrote in a May 12 letter. ``The country has
plunged to the bottom politically, economically and socially. The
moral decay is the most deplorable.''
   Letters dated June 8 and July 19 attacked Sein Lwin by reference
to his party position, for ``turning a blind eye'' to ``all kinds
of human rights violations.''
   Army troops reportedly called in by Sein Lwin _ and riot troops
he is widely said to have commanded _ brutally supressed student
demonstrations in the capital earlier this year. Aung Gyi, giving
gruesome detail of rapes and beatings, claimed that 283 persons
died in the riots.
   Aung Gyi was in turn sharply criticized by Ne Win and delegates
to the recent party congress at which Ne Win offered his resignation
   Sein Win, who joined the Associated Press shortly after being
released from prison in 1968, earlier served on the executive board
of the International Press Institute. When publishing The Guardian,
Sein Win also founded the first national news agency in Burma.
   His first jail term of one year came in the waning days of the
civilian government of Prime Minister U Nu. Along with thousands of
other political prisoners, he was incarcerated for two years by the
Ne Win regime.
   On Friday, meanwhile, anti-government posters were affixed to
Burma's holiest shrine, the Shwedagon Pagoda, in the first known
public protest since Sein Lwin took over power.
   Pilgrims returning from worship at the soaring, gold-laden
shrine said a small number of young students mounted water tanks at
the Shwedagon on Thursday evening, giving anti-government speeches
and shouting slogans.
   The students returned before noon Friday but there were no
reports of violence or confrontation with authorities.
</TEXT>
