<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CentralAmerica-Glance     07-30 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Central America-Glance,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central American Peace Plan at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the main goals of the peace plan for Central America,
signed Aug. 7 by the presidents of Costa Rica, Guatemala, Honduras,
El Salvador and Nicaragua:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Negotiated cease-fires in Nicaragua and El Salvador, which are
both engaged in civil wars, and in Guatemala and Honduras, which
are trying to suppress leftist insurgencies.
   The conflicts in the four countries have claimed a total of
nearly 200,000 lives in the past decade.
   _Amnesties for political offenders in all four countries.
Nicaragua and El Salvador have declared limited, conditional
amnesties for their political prisoners.
   The plan does not clearly define to whom amnesty should be
granted _ political prisoners, armed opponents or both. Therefore,
application of amnesty differs in the five countries.
   _Democratization, defined by the plan as meaning full freedom of
the press and other media and the right of dissident political
groups to assemble and promote their views.
   Direct or indirect political repression continues in all the
countries except Costa Rica, which has had peace and democracy
since 1948.
   _Lifting of emergency or martial law. At the time the plan was
signed, only Nicaragua had such a law. But Amnesty International
and other human rights organizations say restrictions on freedom
were also enforced in the other countries through fear of execution
by right-wing death squads or leftist terrorists.
   _An end to all outside aid to the region's insurgents. Until
February, the United States provided military and humanitarian aid
to the Contras battling the Nicaraguan government, which in turn
receives military aid from Soviet bloc countries. El Salvador's
president Jose Napoleon Duarte claims Nicaragua is also channeling
aid to leftists trying to overthrow his government.
   _An end to the use of any country's territory by groups or
individuals seeking the overthrow of a neighboring government. This
is aimed primarily at Honduras, where the Nicaraguan rebels have
maintained camps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
