<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Jordan-Parliament 1stLd-Writethru a0527 07-30 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jordan-Parliament, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Dissolves Jordan's Lower House of Parliament</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with king planning speech Sunday on
latest developments, council could replace lower house, history of
the institution, including other times it was dissolved. No pickup.
^By JAMAL HALABY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associted Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein today signed a decree
dissolving the lower house of Parliament, the official news agency
Petra said.
   Petra also said the king ``will deliver an important speech'' on
Sunday. He is expected to outline Jordan's new policy toward the
Palestinians.
   Dissolving the Chamber of Deputies appeared to be another
attempt to distance Jordan from Palestinian affairs in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. On Thursday, King
Hussein canceled a $1.3 billion development plan for Palestinians
in the occupied territories.
   Israel captured the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip
from Egypt during the 1967 Middle East war. Half the 60 members of
Jordan's Chamber of Deputies were from the West Bank.
   Information Minister Hani Khasawneh said a ``consultative
council might replace the lower house of Parliament within the next
few days.''
   Another Jordanian official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said dissolving the lower house will give the Palestine Liberation
Organization greater responsiblity over West Bank and Gaza Strip
affairs.
   ``This move is similar to the king's decision of a funding cut
and we expecting other similar moves in the next few days,'' the
official said.
   Khasawneh said Jordan intended to close all joint institutions
with the Palestinians, including a joint Jordanian-Palestinian
committee which finances educational and other services in the
occupied lands.
   He said Jordan's changing relationship with Palestinians was
aimed at ``avoiding friction'' between this country and the PLO.
   Since December, the occupied lands have been wracked by
Palestinian protests against Israeli rule. Since the uprising began
Dec. 8, more than 230 Palestinians and four Israelis have been
killed. Leaders of the uprising are tied to the PLO, which helps
finance the protests.
   The lower house of Jordan's Parliament was first elected in
April 1967, two months before the Middle East war. It was suspended
in 1974, following the Rabat summit resolution which recognized the
PLO as the only legitimate representative world's 5 million
Palestinians.
   In 1978, a National Consultative Council composed of 80 members
replaced the Chamber of Deputies. In January 1984, a royal decree
reinstated the lower house and it remained in session until today.
   When Jordan canceled the development plant, government officials
said the move was designed to hand over more responsibility for the
1.5 million Arabs in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to the
PLO.
   Meron Benvenisti, an Israeli expert on the West Bank, said he
thought the move was the first step toward a decision by King
Hussein eventually to cut ties with the occupied lands altogether.
   ``He wants to see how people react. But ultimately he has no
choice but to cut ties,'' Benvenisti, head of the West Bank Data
Bank, a U.S.-funded research project, said earlier this week.
   ``If he doesn't, he gives money to people who in the long run
are his enemies,'' said Benvenisti, referring to a growing
anti-Jordanian slant among West Bank Palestinians.
   Palestinian leaders in the West Bank were divided on the impact
of the cancellation of the development plan. Some said it would
seriously hurt residents already struggling financially because of
the uprising.
   Israeli officials said the cancellation of the development plan
would have no practical effect because it existed primarily on
paper.
   According to Article 34 in the Jordanian Constitution, the king
has the power to dissolve the Chamber of Deputies. A Parliament
with members from both side of the River Jordan was originally
conceived in 1950 when the late King Abdullah, King Hussein's
grandfather, united the two banks.
</TEXT>
