<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1208EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Blacks-Jews 1stLd-Writethru a0538 07-30 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blacks-Jews, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0538,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Incidents, Articles Address Anti-Semitism Among Chicago Blacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 25th graf, `Eugene Kennedy ...' to change editorial to
essay.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This city, long branded one of the nation's most
segregated, is also being labeled anti-Semitic as black leaders
come under fire for failing to challenge the strident and widely
publicized airing of simmering grievances against Jews.
   At the center of the controversy is former mayoral aide Steve
Cokely, who once claimed among other things that ``the AIDS
epidemic is a result of doctors, especially Jewish ones, who inject
AIDS into blacks.''
   Cokely's statements, made during lectures before he held his
City Hall post, did not gain widespread attention until the city's
newspapers published them in April.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer dismissed Cokely five days later. The delay
dismayed Chicago's Jewish community, but some black leaders rallied
to Cokely's defense, saying his firing was outrageous and
symptomatic of the power Jews exert over blacks.
   Louis Farrakhan, who heads the Chicago-based Nation of Islam,
said Cokely's remarks offended Jewish leaders ``because the truth
hurts.'' Farrakhan, whose group claims 10,000 members, gained
attention with his own anti-Semitic stance in 1984, when he
supported Jesse Jackson's first presidential bid.
   Only a handful of prominent blacks have come forward to denounce
Farrakhan or Cokely.
   From others has come a silence that has aggravated tensions
between blacks and Jews and brought the city under scrutiny
recently in The New York Times and the New Republic and Chicago
magazines.
   ``What the Cokely incident really reveals is the unfortunate
divisions that have occurred in Chicago's black community since the
death of (Mayor) Harold Washington,'' said Clarence Page, a black
columnist and an editor of the Chicago Tribune.
   Washington, who had many Jewish allies, was the city's first
black mayor and fought a long battle against white aldermen for
control of the city's government.
   Sawyer, also black, was elected largely by anti-Washington
whites on the City Council after Washington died last year; he
hired Cokely as part of his struggle to gain black support.
   ``Anytime a community feels itself under siege and divided, its
leaders embrace their own, even when they are people they might
otherwise want to distance themselves from,'' Page said.
   ``This is one case where the community has behaved better than
its leaders.''
   He noted that when the Tribune polled voters after the Cokely
firing, only 8 percent of blacks said Cokely should have kept his
job.
   The traditional alliance between blacks and Jews, solidified
during the civil rights movement, has been strained by other
statements, incidents and divergent opinions in recent years.
   Among them are Jackson's ``Hymietown'' remark in referring to
New York during the 1984 campaign and Israel's continuing sale of
weapons to South Africa.
   ``Chicago is neither more anti-Semitic than any other city, nor
more anti-Semitic than in the past. In fact, the black community is
less anti-Semitic than its whites,'' Page said.
   Cokely himself has continued lecturing and did not respond to
telephone requests for an interview last week.
   On Thursday, an interracial group of ministers, rabbis and
civil-rights leaders that has been meeting informally since the
Cokely incident called for more dialogue and stronger leadership.
   ``Civic and political leaders must move quickly and forcefully
to denounce all expressions of anti-Semitism, racism and other
forms of bigotry to prevent them from gaining legitimacy,'' the
group's statement said.
   To promote understanding, the group announced a program of
speakers to appear in churches and synagogues and stress the
``historic ties'' between blacks and Jews.
   Chicago's Jewish community supported Washington in far greater
numbers than other white ethnics, and Washington reciprocated _
many of his top officials were Jewish. But Jews clearly have been
upset by the Cokely incident.
   Its impact likely was increased by other events. A Holocaust
memorial in suburban Skokie was defaced, and windows were smashed
at Jewish shops and synagogues here on the 49th anniversary of
``Crystal Night,'' when the Nazis carried out similar attacks in
Germany.
   ``Past cooperation is evidently no guarantee of present
understanding or future compassion,'' said Rabbi Robert Marx, a
member of the group.
   ``Do we speak for all Jews and all blacks? Of course not,'' he
said. ``There is much work to be done in both of our communities to
build bridges and remove fences.''
   Eugene Kennedy, a Loyola University psychology professor, argued
in an essay in Tuesday's New York Times that the Cokely affair has
brought about ``the ugliest experience that the city has suffered
in a long time.''
   He said some black politicians have shown a willingness to
exploit the Cokely incident ``to tap into what they identify as a
current of anti-Jewish feeling in their community.''
   ``There's no question about the fact that in the black community
here there are strong negative feelings towards many Jewish
people,'' said Lu Palmer, an influential local radio commentator
and self-described black nationalist.
   ``But whether Chicago is worse than anywhere else, I honestly
don't know. My suspicion is you wouldn't find much difference
wherever you went.''
</TEXT>
