<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-PemexChief     07-30 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Pemex Chief,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Pemex Director Freed From Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jorge Diaz Serrano, former head of the
government oil monopoly, was freed from prison today after serving
five years of a 10-year sentence for fraud.
   Diaz Serrano, an ex-senator, left the Southern Penitentiary
accompanied by his wife and two sons and maintaining his innocence,
as he has throughout the highly publicized case. ``I am returning
to freedom, but not because there has been justice,'' he told
reporters.
   A circuit court in March reduced his sentence to five years,
saying Diaz Serrano was not dangerous. The Supreme Court upheld the
reduction on July 18.
   The cases of Diaz Serrano and former Mexico City police chief
Arturo Durazo Moreno were centerpieces of President Miguel de la
Madrid's ``moral renovation'' campaign in the early 1980s.
   Diaz Serrano was convicted in 1983 of defrauding the state oil
company Pemex of $34 million through the purchase of two natural
gas tankers. He was sentenced to 10 years in prison and fined the
equivalent of $58 million.
   Diaz Serrano headed Pemex from 1976 to 1981, the oil boom years
of former President Jose Lopez Portillo. After leaving Pemex, Diaz
Serrano was elected senator from the northern state of Sonora.
Under the de la Madrid administration, Congress stripped him from
his immunity from prosecution.
   His lawyer, Enrique Mendoza Morales, said Diaz Serrano doesn't
have the money to pay the $58 million fine, but under Mexican law,
cannot be held in prison because of his inability to pay.
   Mendoza Morales said the government has confiscated about a $1
million in assets from Diaz Serrano, including property in the
resort cities of Cuernavaca and Acapulco and an art collection.
   The case of Durazo Moreno, accused of extortion and illegal arms
possession, is still pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
