<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Georgia-Swindall Bjt   07-30 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia-Swindall, Bjt,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two-Term Republican Congressman In Trouble At Home On Loan
Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug questions dominate a bitter contest for an
Atlanta congressonal seat, with the incumbent admitting he
considered using laundered drug money to finance his home and a
challenger saying he might consider legalizing drugs.
   Rep. Pat Swindall, a two-term Republican whose philosophy is
largely in tune with that of the religious right, is unopposed in
his party's Aug. 9 primary.
   The front-runner in a three-way Democratic contest for the seat
in the affluent 4th District is widely considered to be Ben Jones,
who played mechanic Cooter on the ``Dukes of Hazzard.'' He took 47
percent of the vote against Swindall in a 1986 challenge.
   Jones has acknowledged telling a Young Democrats meeting at the
University of Georgia in May that he might consider legalizing
drugs. But he added that he told the group that would be an option
``only after a massive effort to truly eradicate drugs.''
   Jones has complained that his views have been distorted, and his
campaign ads stress his opposition to drugs.
   One of his opponents, lawyer Nick Moraitakis, who has been
campaigning for more than a year, said the remark was ``irrational,
irresponsible and ridiculous.''
   John Stembler, a theater operator and last-minute entry in the
Democratic race, said he intended to hit the drug question hard in
TV ads before the primary.
   Jones said he doesn't think the charge that he is soft on drugs
will hurt his chances. ``The truth always comes out and I think
this tactic backfires,'' he said.
   Swindall, 37, an Atlanta lawyer and businessman, won the
congressional seat in 1984 by defeating Democratic Rep. Elliott
Levitas. The election turned, in part, on Swindall's charge that
the incumbent talked a conservative game at home but voted with the
liberals in Washington.
   In office, Swindall has stressed his ties with his church and
frequently sided with the religious right on issues such as
abortion.
   But a 12,500-square-foot, $1 million house he built has cast
dark clouds over his political career.
   First, there was bad publicity about liens filed against the
property for unpaid bills. Swindall said the money should have been
paid by the contractor.
   Then, an Atlanta businessman with whom he discussed a mortgage
loan was indicted by a federal grand jury on money-laundering
charges.
   Swindall was called to testify before the grand jury in February
and told reporters at the time he returned a $150,000 check from
the businessman, Charles LeChasney, because he was concerned that
LeChasney and another man _ later identified as an undercover
Internal Revenue Service agent _ were trying to use him to launder
money.
   However, a government videotape, the contents of which were
obtained by reporters, showed Swindall continued pursuing an
$850,000 loan, even after being told it might be financed with drug
money, until he was informed by the undercover agent that a
go-between could not be used and that Swindall would have to accept
the proceeds in person and sign a receipt.
   The congressman told supporters he was ``embarrassed and
ashamed'' of dealing with the men, but that he did not violate the
law because he ultimately did not take the money.
   ``I entertained things that were illegal and I entertained
things that were wrong,'' he said in June. ``But I thank God I
rejected (the loan).''
   Jones, 47, said he isn't focusing on Swindall's problems.
   ``I'm just going to keep on doing what I've been doing _ talking
about the issues, the differences between he and I and trying to
take the highest road possible. ... His other problems are simply
there and I don't intend to talk about them,'' Jones said.
   Swindall's campaign consultant, Robb Austin, said the loan
consideration will be a factor in the election but added, ``This is
a conservative district and Pat, without question, has represented
the views in the district.''
</TEXT>
