<DOCNO> AP880730-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Tibet     07-30 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Tibet,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Criticized for Silence on Tibet</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private human rights organization stepped up
criticism of the Reagan administration on Saturday, saying it has
failed to raise with Chinese authorities questions of torture,
political arrests and other human rights abuses in Tibet.
   President Reagan's ``decision not to speak up on the subject of
Tibet when he met with China's foreign minister in March, just
after the renewed violence in Lhasa (Tibet) is indefensible,'' Asia
Watch said in its second report on the issue in half a year.
   Washington's silence ``has enabled the government of China to
maintain policies in Tibetan areas ... that go against the grain of
prevailing American sentiment on internationally-recognized human
rights and against the provisions of U.S. laws that embody those
sentiments,'' the report said.
   ``U.S. government inaction, combined with China's decision to
bar, with a few scattered exceptions, the international media and
concerned observers from Tibet, has contributed to the creation of
a climate in which the abuse of rights can proceed with little
regard for international opinion, international norms or ...
international obligations which China has accepted.''
   The State Department said it had not seen the Asia Watch report
and would not comment.
   The United States recognizes Tibet, in a remote Himalayan border
region, as part of China. Asia Watch said it takes no stand on the
issue of independence for Tibet.
   When Chinese Foreign Minister Wu Xueqian visited Washington last
March, ``the only real problem that the administration seems to
have perceived in Sino-American relations ... was China's position
in the Persian Gulf War, including its sales of Silkworm missiles
to Iran,'' Asia Watch said.
   An apparent decision not to take up the Tibetan issue with Wu
was ``particularly unfortunate,'' it said, because Wu visited
shortly after March riots in Tibet that were ``far more serious
than the fall disturbances in the Tibetan capital, which had at
least managed to elicit some concerned comment from the
administration ...
   ``The evidence strongly indicates that human rights conditions
in Tibet have deteriorated since last fall; government brutality in
the March violence seems to have exceeded the level of violence
during the fall; the number of arrests seems to be higher; the
torture in prison continues.''
   The report noted that when Chinese Vice Premier Tian Jiyun
visited the White House and State Department last May, again there
was ``no indication that the administration made any attempt to
broach the Tibetan issue.''
   Asia Watch quoted reports from various sources that as many as
50 people died after daylong rioting involving up to 10,000
Tibetans in street battles with security forces on March 5, the
last day of a Great Prayer Festival in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., co-chairman of the Congressional
Human Rights Caucus, said the report confirmed information the
caucus has been receiving since the unrest began last year in Tibet.
   Improved U.S.-Chinese relations, while in the interest of both
countries, cannot occur ``in the face of continued Chinese
violations of Tibetan human rights,'' Lantos said.
   ``The Chinese authorities must understand that just as the
American people have insisted on the observance of human rights by
the Soviet Union as a condition of improved U.S.-Soviet relations,
so Chinese observance of Tibetan human rights is a precondition for
further improvement in U.S.-China relations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880730-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-ReaganText     07-30 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan Text,810</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of President Reagan's weekly
radio address, delivered from Camp David, Md.:
   My fellow Americans, what a moment of hope it was one year ago
when Central American leaders concluded their meeting in Guatemala.
   A Sandinista government of Nicaragua, a communist regime,
fighting a civil war against 15,000 Nicaraguan freedom fighters
opposed to their oppression, agreed to a series of sweeping
democratic reforms. If carried out, those reforms would have ended
the killing and brought peace to Nicaragua and Central America. It
would also have meant that Nicaragua would have last joined the
family of free democratic nations.
   At first, there were a few hopeful signs to much media fanfare:
the opposition newspaper in Nicaragua, La Prensa, was reopened;
independent radio stations were allowed to broadcast again; a few
political prisoners were released, and political groups were
allowed more latitude. Most important, Sandinistas finally agreed
to the freedom fighters' request for direct negotiations for a
peaceful democratic settlement.
   Now, the main reason the Sandinistas agreed to those steps a
year ago was the steady progress of the freedom fighters including
important battlefield victories like the one at Los Minos. But
tragically, t the very moment when continued strength and
determination by the United States might have meant the continued
success of the peace plan, the United States House of
Representatives decided, and by only a very narrow margin, to
refuse my request for further effective aid to the freedom fighters.
   This, of course, removed the principal prod _ the military
victories and popular success of the freedom fighters to Sandinista
participation in the peace plan _ and sent an immediate signal of
American weakness to the communists.
   This failure to support the freedom fighters has had costly and
sad consequences _ just how costly and sad we've seen during the
past few weeks. Communist Sandinista leader Daniel Ortega has been
visiting Castro in Cuba and voicing solidarity with the tyrant who
has brought so much sadness and misery to that country. While in
Nicaragua, a renewed attack on political descent is being led by
the head of the secret police, Tomas Borge, a dedicated communist
and grim, hardened repressor of human rights whose office,
according to our Commission on Organized Crime, has also been
actively engaged in the international drug trade.
   Acting under the orders of the communist leaders and Borge's
supervision, Sandinista police and goon squads have brutally broken
up a peaceful demonstration by 3,000 Nicaraguans. Opposition
leaders were jailed or beaten and now sentenced to prison.
Political religious liberties have again been curtailed. The
communists ordered the Catholic archbishop to shut down the
Catholic radio station. And for almost two weeks, the independent
newspaper, La Prensa, was refused permission to publish and the
American Ambassador was expelled. And yet, while the cutoff of aid
to the freedom fighters was a dreadful mistake, getting the cause
of peace and freedom back on track, not recrimination, must now be
our goal.
   There is a chance for a real bipartisan consensus in support of
renewed Contra aid. Indeed, one of its strong supporters has
recently been named to be the vice presidential candidate of the
Democratic party.
   Senator Bob Dole intends soon to offer legislation to renew
effective assistance to the freedom fighters. The final details are
being worked out, and I urge the members of the Senate to support
the aid package and I also asked the House of Representatives to
move speedily and favorably on the Senate legislation.
   Meanwhile, we continue to pursue aggressively our diplomatic
efforts with the Central American democracies. So much is at stake.
   A few years ago, there were those who said the cause of freedom
and democracy was lost in El Salvador. Well, perhaps some of you
remember that incredible scene when the people of that country
defied communist threats and bullets to march to the polls and vote
for democracy. The American aid package that helped make democracy
victorious in El Salvador passed by only two votes in the House,
but pass it did and democracy did come.
   A few weeks ago, both Vice President Bush and I visited the
bedside of one of the heroes of that struggle _ President Duarte of
El Salvador. President Duarte's had no easy life. He has been
continually threatened by extremists of both left and right. His
daughter was kidnapped by communist guerrillas.
   And now, while in a desperate struggle with cancer, he continues
to lead his nation on the high road to democracy. And I cannot tell
you how deeply moved Vice President Bush and I were by our visit to
this brave and remarkable man. And how determined we both were that
his dream for his people and all the peoples of Central America
should be made a reality _ the dream of peace and freedom for every
man, woman, and child.
   Until next week, thanks for listening, and God bless you.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
