<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HopeDiamond     07-30 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hope Diamond,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vault Opens, Hope Diamond Back On Display</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vault containing the Hope Diamond popped
open Saturday after being stuck shut for four days, hiding one of
the Smithsonian Museum of Natural History's most popular
attractions.
   Crowds gathering around the 44.4 carat blue diamond acquired by
the museum in 1958 were confronted with a printed sign saying the
diamond could not be displayed.
   Museum officials said they believe the timer on the vault
holding the diamond may have malfunctioned.
   ``Mechanics are looking at it, and the men that maintain the
safe are checking it out,'' museum spokesman Tom Harney said. ``We
should be able to tell next week what went wrong.''
   The vault opened shortly before the museum's 10 a.m. scheduled
opening Saturday, Harney said. The diamond is kept behind a thick
layer of bulletproof glass covered by a heavy, non-transparent door
that a timer opens so the gem can be displayed.
   The museum had trouble with the safe once before, in 1967. But
that problem was resolved when museum officials discovered that a
substitute guard had simply forgotten how to make it open.
   Despite the possibility the vault could jam shut again, museum
officials said they were locking up the priceless gem at the close
of business Saturday.
</TEXT>
