<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-DemocratsText     07-30 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Democrats Text,750</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address, given by Sen. Carl Levin
of Michigan:
   I'm pleased that the Senate and the House have passed drought
relief legislation. This is an important first step in addressing a
situation that threatens America's farmers and affects every one of
us.
   But today I want to talk abut two other bills passed by
Contgress _ ono. I want to tell you why.
   The first of these is the defense bill. President reagan
requested about $300 billion in spending for the nation's defense
in 1989. the Senate and the House approved the total amount the
president asked for, but we differed with the president on just how
we should spend that money to make the nation more secure.
   As in the past, President Reagan overemphasized nuclear weapons
and Star Wars at the expense of our conventional forces. He also
proposed actions which would make effective arms control harder to
achieve and maintain.
   Let me give you an example. President Reagan requested almost $5
billion for St ar Wars, a 24 percent increase over last year's
level. At the same time, he proposed cutting the Army's ammunition
purchases by over 10 percent. Those are the wrong priorities. They
waste money on redundant nuclear weapons and exotic space weapons
research while shortchanging needed conventional capabilities that
would make nuclear war less likely.
   That is why Congress rearranged the spending priorities in the
bill. We held Star Wars spending at last year's level and used the
savings to increase spending on needed Army ammunition and initiate
a program to develop new weapons that can stop modern Soviet tanks.
   We also placed limits on how star Wars funds can be spent to
ensure that the United States does not violate the Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty we signed with the Soviets. The last thing we need
is a new arms race in space, especially while we are trying to
conclude a treaty that would cut both sides' existing nuclear
arsenals by 50 percent.
   Unfortunately, a few of his advisers urged President Reagan to
veto the bill Congress passed and to go back to his original
defense priorities. that was bad advise. After all, even his own
secretary of defense and national security adviser supported the
bill.
   Another important bill which deserves the president's support is
the legislation which requires companies employing 100 or more
workers to give 60 days notice prior to a plant closing or a major
layoff.
   President Reagan concedes the notifying of workers who are about
to lose their jobs is ``the humane thing to do.''
   But President Reagan says that he thinks that providing notice
to workers should be voluntary. But, of course, it already is.
   This bill isn't aimed at companies that are going to do the
decent thing anyway. It is aimed at companies, like one I know in
Michigan, that told its workers on a Friday afternoon that they
were being laid off for two weeks.
   But then, over the weekend, workers living near the plant saw it
being dismantled, its machinery carted off on flatbed trucks.
   That is how 130 workers discovered they were losing their jobs.
Of that number, 45 had been with the company between 30 and 40
years.
   Worst of all, the plant's owners knew that they were going to
shut it down for the previous six months. They intentionally kept
their employees in the dark, intentionally kept them from making
the plans necessary for cushioning the blow and starting anew.
   The advance notification bill would prevent human tragedies like
that. It would also give workers and the states and towns in which
they live one final chance ot try to save the plant from closing
down. And these are reasons the president should support it.
   One more point. Governor Dukakis supports this bill and pushed
through a similar law in Massachusetts. But we haven't heard from
Vice President Bush on this bill. Where is George?
   Most Americans favor this advance notification bill. But does
Vice President Bush?
   These two bills, the 1989 defense bill and the plant closing
notification, are very different. But taken together they advance a
goal we all share: security and dignity for all Americans and for
our country.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
