<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Talks,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Envoy Says Iran Would Accept Talks with Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Peace Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian envoy said
Saturday that Iran is willing to hold direct talks with Iraq if
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar deems it necessary
to achieving peace.
   ``I ... officially declare that there is no obstacle or problem
hindering direct talks with Iraq,'' Iran's deputy foreign minister,
Ali Mohammed Besharati told a press conference.
   Besharati arrived in Abu Dhabi earlier Saturday on a tour of
Persian Gulf states. It is the first such visit by an Iranian
official since Iran's July 18 acceptance of U.N. Resolution 598,
calling for a cease-fire in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war.
   Iraq has insisted on direct talks with Iran before a cease-fire.
Iran has rejected this but indicated it would be willing to hold
face-to-face talks after a cease-fire.
   When asked whether Iran was prepared to conduct direct talks
with Iraq before the cease-fire, Besharati replied, ``We thought of
cease-fire and peace. In order to reach this, we cooperated with
U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, and if de Cuellar
sees it as necessary to reach this end, we will accept it.''
   Besharati spoke in Farsi, and an interpreter gave the English
translation.
   When asked to clearly state whether Iran accepts direct talks,
he said ``I am hereby the deputy foreign minister of Iran
officially declaring that there is no obstacle or problem hindering
direct talks with Iraq.''
   There was no immediate comment from Iranian officials at the
United Nations, where Perez de Cuellar is holding separate meetings
with the warring sides. Calls to the Iranian Mission went
unanswered Saturday.
   Perez de Cuellar met earlier Saturday with Iranian Foreign
Minister Ali Akbar Velayati before adjourning talks for the
weekend. Velayati refused comment on the meeting.
   Perez de Cuellar told reporters he is ``maintaining pressure on
all sides in order to obtain a quick way out of the present
situation'' _ referring to the deadlock on face-to-face talks.
   Diplomatic sources at the United Nations said that Saudi Arabia,
a major supporter of Iraq, has joined other nations trying to
pressure Baghdad to compromise and agree to a cease-fire before
direct talks.
   Perez de Cuellar called reports of Saudi pressure
``imaginative.'' He said he met Friday with Prince Bandar bin
Sultan bin Badul Aziz, Saudi Arabia's ambassador to Washington.
   ``He expressed the support of his country for my efforts. They
are playing a role,'' he told reporters. Prince Bandar also met
Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz on Friday.
   Iraq's former U.N. ambassador, Riyadh al-Qaysi, denied reports
of pressure.
   ``I tell you categorically there is no such pressure on Iraq. No
such pressure is there on Iraq from any quarter,'' he told
reporters outside U.N. Headquarters.
</TEXT>
