<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-30 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Think you recognize that shopper? Don't say hello
yet _ it might be Uncle Charlie.
   The 16th Street Mall is going to be seeded with plastic
sculptures made from life, and you too can get in on the action.
   The sculptures are ``life casts,'' in which artists take a mold
from the body of a living person, cast it in plastic, then dress it
and paint it to look real down to the fingerprints.
   ``My boss is a bit of a crazy man, and he had heard of this,''
said Margaret Sillstrop, researcher and coordinator for the project.
   The project is developer David French's attempt to inject some
fun into downtown, Sillstrop said.
   She said she's recruited people on the mall who look as if they
would make interesting sculptures. French's company also plans a
lottery, with the winner immortalized in fiberglass.
   The 20-pound sculptures will be sold at cost, $3,500, to
businesses on the mall. Sillstrop hopes to have eight or nine up by
Sept. 1 and 15-20 by December. The sculptures will be bolted down
and will be removed at night and during snow or rain.
   Sillstrop's 69-year-old uncle, Charlie Shugarts, was the first
model for sculptors Porter Arnill and Greg Lamb. The sculptors and
painters Quang Ho and Jay Moore can turn out a finished product in
80 hours.
   On Thursday, Shugarts' likeness was put on a bench as Shugarts
watched.
   ``My brother-in-law turned to me and said, `I hope you look that
good in your casket,''' Shugarts said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRANGER, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1,000 nudists gathering for a
convention here this weekend hope their contribution to the economy
isn't as invisible as their clothing.
   Or as visible as their skins.
   Planners of the 35th annual Midwest Sunbathing Association
Convention bought $3,000 in $2 bills and are selling them at cost
to campers, who will spend them when they get dressed and go to
town.
   The MSA convention at Sunny Haven Park is similar to any other
large convention, except that participants conduct most of their
business in the nude.
   Like other American Sunbathing Association clubs, Sunny Haven
stresses nudism and family. It has been located here for 41 years.
   ``Most clubs limit the numbers of singles they admit,'' said Sue
Ward, president of MSA. ``Our main focus is on couples and family.
(The ideal member) comes to us with lots of little kids.''
   For most campers, the convention is a chance to relax and get
reacquainted.
   ``These are people that we only see once a year,'' said Pirie
Cleveland, a 21-year ASA member. ``They're like family, the best
friends in the world.''
   The group has traditions that are carried on each. For instance,
anyone can have their club's logo drawn on their posterior.
   ``It's fun and makes you immediately identifiable,'' said Diane,
Sunny Haven treasurer. She declined to reveal her last name.
   Nudists typically don't use last names at gatherings, she said,
adding, ``It's a constriction society has forced on us.''
</TEXT>
