<DOCNO> AP880730-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PeaceTalks Bjt   07-30 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Peace Talks, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Week Status Report: Progress Slow</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly eight years of conflict on
the battlefield, Iran and Iraq seemed locked in dispute at the
United Nations last week over Iraq's demand for face-to-face talks
before a cease-fire.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who brought the
foreign ministers of the two countries to New York last week,
insisted the obstacles to an accord were merely procedural. He said
he hopes to announce a cease-fire date sometime this week.
   But despite the secretary-general's optimism, progress has
appeared slow and halting.
   Movement toward the current talks began July 18, when Iran
reversed a year-long stance and said it would accept a U.N.
resolution calling for an immediate cease-fire.
   The Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's spiritual leader, said
opting for peace without victory and overthrow of the Iraqi regime
was like ``swallowing poison.''
   The bitter broth was sweet news to the international community.
But it fueled Iraqi suspicions that Iran was insincere and only
sought a temporary truce to rebuild its forces.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz insisted there could be no
cease-fire or further negotiations without first holding
face-to-face talks, which he says would offer proof of Iran's
sincerity.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati rejected the demand.
He said Friday there would be no direct talks before a cease-fire
and rejected what he called Iraq's efforts to delay a peace
settlement.
   The issue was further complicated Saturday with remarks by
Iran's deputy foreign minister, Ali Mohammed Besharati, who told a
news conference in Abu Dhabi that Iran would participate in direct
talks if Perez de Cuellar asked it to.
   Here is where the U.N. talks stand now:
   _Points of Agreement:
   Both sides unconditionally accept Resolution 598, a 10-point
plan including an immediate cease-fire and troop withdrawal, a
prisoner exchange, formal peace talks and a commission to determine
which side was the aggressor in the war.
   Both agreed to hold immediate, separate talks with the
secretary-general on implementing the resolution. They agree the
secretary-general will set dates for the different phases of the
plan.
   A team of U.N. military experts has visited both capitals to
work out details of a cease-fire, and another is investigating
prisoner-of-war issues in both countries.
   _Points of Disagreement:
   Iraq insists on direct talks in New York before a cease-fire,
while Iran rejects direct talks at this time.
   Iraq also demands that before a cease-fire goes into effect,
Iran promise not to attack Iraqi and neutral shipping in the
Persian Gulf. It also calls for the United Nations to dredge the
disputed Shatt Al-Arab waterway, the southern boundary between the
two nations.
   Iran will make no commitments on these issues.
   _Participants:
   Perez de Cuellar: A 67-year-old Peruvian diplomat, Perez de
Cuellar is known for diligence and determination rather than
dynamism. He is the first Latin American to hold the post of
secretary-general, now in his second five-year term. He is
considered a patient, skillful negotiator.
   Iraq's Tariq Aziz: Appointed in 1981 as foreign minister, the
51-year-old Aziz is a long-time colleague of President Sadam
Hussein in Iraq's Baath Party. He sometimes is referred to as
Hussein's right-hand man.
   Aziz, a Christian, is considered one of the most eloquent
spokesmen of the Iraqi government.
   Iran's Ali Akbar Velayati: A 43-year-old pediatrician, Velayati
trained at Johns Hopkins University in Maryland. In Iran he has
been active in establishing relief centers and clinics.
   In 1977, Velayati denounced the Shah and was arrested for
anti-government activities. He was active in welcoming Khomeini to
Iran and later was named by Khomeini as his representative for
national reconstruction.
   Since Tuesday, Perez de Cuellar has met five times with Velayati
and three times with Aziz. Talks are scheduled to begin again
Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
