<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-LeaderReplaced     07-30 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Leader Replaced,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regional Party Chief Removed After Protesters Demanded his Ouster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party committee in the Volga River
region of Kuybyshev on Saturday removed its leader after
demonstrations by thousands of residents demanding his resignation.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said the Kuybyshev
committee, at a plenary meeting, relieved Yevgeny F. Muravyev of
his duties as party first secretary ``in connection with his
retirement.'' The brief dispatch did not elaborate on the reason
for Muravyev's removal and did not mention the residents' protest
campaign.
   In an indication of high-level Kremlin concern for the
situation, Tass reported that a member of the country's ruling
Politburo, Vitaly I. Vorotnikov, spoke at the Kuybyshev party
meeting.
   Moscow-based members of the informal political group Democratic
Union reported that an estimated 40,000 Kuybyshev residents rallied
July 21 to demand replacement of Muravyev. The residents also
threatened a strike in the important industrial region, where
aircraft, locomotives, tractors, chemicals and textiles are
produced, the Democratic Union reported.
   A protest in Kuybyshev on June 22 involved 10,000 people, the
political group said.
   The demonstrators complained that the 59-year-old Muravyev was
responsible for food shortages, dirty streets, poor transportation
and unfair distribution of housing in Kuybyshev, a city of 1.2
million people 530 miles southeast of Moscow.
   Muravyev, an engineer, was appointed Kuybyshev first secretary
in 1979. He is also a member of the nationwide party Central
Committee and legislature, the Supreme Soviet.
   Tass said the party committee replaced Muravyev with V.G.
Afonin, the head of the Central Committee's chemical industry
department.
</TEXT>
