<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz-Nicaragua     07-30 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Nicaragua,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Trip Angers Sandinistas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz-Central America,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz's
trip to Central America this week has angered leaders of the
leftist Sandinista government.
   The state news media called Shultz's planned meeting in
Guatemala City Monday with the foreign ministers of El Salvador,
Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala another example of U.S.
``aggression'' against Nicaragua.
   Nicaragua was not invited to attend the meeting, at which Shultz
is expected to endorse a ``statement of principles'' on what is
needed to get a Central American peace plan moving again.
   The plan, drawn up by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, is
aimed at negotiating an end to the war in Nicaragua and leftist
guerrilla wars in El Salvador and Honduras.
   The Sandinistas claim Nicaragua has made the most progress in
complying with the plan, even though they say the United States
violated the spirit of the accord this year when it approved
non-lethal aid to the Contra rebels fighting the Nicaraguan
government.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco and other leaders say
Honduras still tolerates the presence of Contra camps in its
territory, and both El Salvador and Guatemala have failed to get
truce negotiations under way with their guerrilla foes.
   ``No one is fulfilling the plan but Nicaragua,'' Tinoco said in
a recent interview. ``It has turned into everyone picking on what
Nicaragua does. We insist all actors and factors accept their quota
of responsibility.''
   The Sandinistas concede that, of the five Central American
countries, Nicaragua made the greatest effort to reach agreement
with its insurgents because it had the most to gain _ influencing
Congress to end U.S. aid to the Contras.
   But Tinoco pointed out the peace plan was signed by five
countries and is binding on all.
   ``This was a promise by five countries, not just Nicaragua,''
Tinoco said, adding that the Sandinistas have made great efforts to
negotiate with Contra leaders _ something they had vowed they would
never do.
   The Sandinistas signed a cease-fire agreement with the Contras
March 23 which has often been violated. Talks for a permanent truce
broke down June 9.
   The government also lifted a national emergency law suspending
individual freedoms, in force since the U.S. began supplying aid to
the rebels in 1981. It loosened restrictions on the opposition
press and released about 1,000 of an estimated 4,000 political
prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
