<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-BeginBirthday     07-30 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Begin Birthday,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Celebrates 75th Birthday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of friends, relatives and former
colleagues flocked to Menachem Begin's small home Saturday to mark
the 75th birthday of the former prime minister, who became a
recluse after his sudden resignation five years ago.
   The steady stream of visitors bearing flowers, a bronze plaque
and dozens of cakes created a small traffic jam on narrow Tzemach
Street near the Jerusalem Forest.
   Security agents screened the guests, who included Benyamin
Netanyahu, the former Israeli ambassador to the United Nations and
a rising star of the Likud bloc that Begin once led. Popular
Israeli singer Yoram Gaon also attended.
   ``He looks great, but of course he should gain weight,'' said
visitor Matti Droblas, an official of the quasi-governmental Jewish
Agency and a friend of Begin's.
   The former prime minister was in good spirits and rose to greet
each visitor by name, Droblas said.
   Begin resigned abruptly in 1983, at the height of Israel's
military involvement in Lebanon. He never told even close friends
why he made the dramatic move, telling the Cabinet only: ``I can't
go on any longer.''
   Aides have said Begin was deeply depressed over Israel's soaring
casualties in Lebanon and by the death of his wife, Aliza, in 1982.
   As visitors streamed into Begin's home, a mother who lost her
25-year-old son in Lebanon held a silent vigil outside. Raya
Harnik, of Jerusalem, whose son Guni was killed on the first day of
the war, said she was shocked that people paid homage to Begin.
   ``It's shameless,'' she said. ``This man caused dozens of young
men not to reach even their twentieth birthdays _ he shouldn't let
the visitors come.
   ``In the middle of the war he just said he couldn't go on any
longer,'' Ms. Harnik said. ``The bereaved parents never had such a
privilege.''
   Begin led Israel's invasion into Lebanon in 1982, begining a
three-year occupation. More than 600 Israeli soldiers were killed
in the war.
   Despite his seclusion, Begin remains a prominent behind-the
scenes political figure. He is deluged daily with mail from
well-wishers and people urging him to write his memoirs, according
to long-time aide Yehiel Kadishai.
   On Friday, Begin gave a rare interview on Israel radio and
invited listeners to share in his birthday ceremonies.
   ``Those who remember and want to come _ come,'' he said.
   The retired leader spends most of his days reading or watching
television with his daughter Leah, a flight attendant who lives
with him.
   Kadishai said Begin ``reads everything in print,'' including
novels and non-fiction in Hebrew and English. His favorite author
is the late Primo Levi, who wrote about the Nazi Holocaust.
   Begin was born in Poland. His parents and a brother were among
the 6 million Jews who were killed by the Nazis during World War II.
   Benjamin Begin, 45, the former prime minister's son, is running
for parliament with the Herut party that his father founded. Herut
is the major partner in the Likud bloc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
