<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru   07-30 0877</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0532,0898</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schultz To Try To Mend Tattered Central American Peace Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `The secretary...' to add that principles not
released publicly. SUBS 5th graf, `The peace...' to add year of
plan. Pick up 6th graf, `Instead, they...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will
try to mend a year-old Central American peace plan now in tatters
when he meets here this week with four of the region's foreign
ministers.
   Shultz's initiative appears aimed at increasing diplomatic
pressure on Nicaragua's Sandinista regime and encouraging four
other countries to pursue a negotiated settlement to the area's
conflicts.
   On Monday, the foreign ministers of Guatemala, Honduras, Costa
Rica and El Salvador _ but not Nicaragua _ will present Shultz with
a ``statement of principles'' the Central American leaders agree
are needed to achieve peace. Nicaragua was not invited to the
meeting.
   The secretary of state is expected to endorse the principles,
which have not been released publicly, before continuing on a
nine-day trip to Argentina, Uruguay, Brazil and Bolivia to discuss
South American problems with the leaders of those countries. Shultz
is then to return to meet with the presidents of Costa Rica, El
Salvador and Honduras.
   The peace plan, signed Aug. 7, 1987, by Guatemala, Costa Rica,
El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua, came apart when the leaders in
January failed to extend its deadlines and abolished an
international commission named to verify progress.
   Instead, they vowed to keep working together toward peace.
   But another meeting of the five presidents to review the plan's
progress, tentatively scheduled for Aug. 7, has been shelved
indefinitely.
   El Salvador still is in the midst of a bloody guerrilla war. A
fragile cease-fire in Nicaragua is broken almost daily, and leftist
insurgencies still smolder in Honduras and Guatemala. Only Costa
Rica is at peace.
   ``There are signs that the United States is finally seeking a
more active diplomatic role in the regional process, and that could
revive the peace process,'' said Deane R. Hinton, the U.S.
ambassador in Costa Rica, in a recent interview.
   He added that the United States is seeking a new policy toward
Nicaragua, which has not been fully defined.
   ``Congress has said we can't pursue our interests the way the
president wanted to pursue them,'' Hinton said, referring to
congressional rejection of President Reagan's last request for aid
to the rebels.
   ``If he (Reagan) cannot provide the Contras the weapons that
they ask for to win their cause, then we'll have to try to find
political ways to bring peace and democracy to the area,'' Hinton
added.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua, apparently anticipating
that Shultz will urge the foreign ministers to condemn the
Sandinista government for its failure to live up to the peace plan,
recently called for reactivation of the international commission to
verify progress of the plan.
   Ortega said his fellow Central American presidents were
unqualified to judge the plan's progress because they themselves
had failed to live up to it.
   The plan was conceived and promoted by President Oscar Arias of
Costa Rica, who in December won the Nobel Peace Prize for the idea.
   The Arias plan sets deadlines for compliance with negotiated
cease-fires, amnesties, democratization, an end to outside aid to
insurgents and the use of one country's territory by rebels from
neighboring nations. All were to be defined and achieved by Nov. 7,
1987 _ a date that came and went with only minimal compliance.
   Arias, who once said he would be the first to condemn those who
did not adhere to the deadlines, said in January that the peace
process should not be measured by a calendar.
   In the months after it was signed, the plan did bring some hopes
of peace in the region. But the hopes were quickly stilled by
events.
   The governments of El Salvador and Guatemala conducted talks
with leaders of their leftist guerrilla movements, but no progress
resulted.
   The Honduran government claimed Contra camps did not exist
inside its territory and that it had no armed opposition _ an
attitude sharply challenged by recent terrorist attacks on U.S.
servicemen stationed in that country.
   Nicaragua allowed the reopening of the opposition newspaper La
Prensa and a Roman Catholic radio station, freed some of its
political prisoners, lifted the national state of emergency and
began talks with the Contras _ something the Sandinistas said they
would never do.
   But the talks, which broke down in early June, produced only a
temporary, frequently broken cease-fire that has been extended
through August. The two sides remain at an impasse on the question
of a permanent peace in their 7-year-old civil war.
   The Sandinistas say they cannot support greater democracy until
the Contras lay down their arms and rejoin Nicaraguan society. But
the rebels insist democracy must be instituted in Nicaragua before
they will give up fighting.
   In the meantime, both sides have hardened their positions.
   The Contras elected a new, more conservative leadership to guide
them. The Sandinistas closed the Catholic radio station
indefinitely and shut down La Prensa for 15 days. They also jailed
dozens of Contra leaders, while expelling U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven other American diplomats.
</TEXT>
