<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CambodiaTalks     07-30 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia Talks,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Says Chances For Peace Slim, Vietnam More Optimistic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom
Sihanouk said Saturday that chances for peace in his country are
``very slim,'' but Vietnam's foreign minister said peace talks last
week broke an impasse in the conflict.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach's optimistic comments on the
talks in Indonesia were reported by the official Vietnam News
Agency.
   Sihanouk, who spoke to reporters after arriving in Beijing from
Bangkok, blamed both Vietnam _ which backs the Cambodian government
_ and the Khmer Rouge _ the largest group in the three-party
resistance coalition _ for blocking peace efforts.
   Sihanouk said the Khmer Rouge was the ``biggest obstacle'' to a
settlement of the 9-year-old Cambodian conflict. But he said the
Khmer Rouge would have to be included in a future Cambodian
government.
   ``You cannot reject them.... Nobody is capable of wiping out the
Khmer Rouge, so we have to try to make them less and less dangerous
by including them in a quadrapartite government,'' he said.
   Thach, who attended the meeting of Cambodia's warring factions
in Bogor, Indonesia, said the talks ended amid bitter clashes but
also some convergence of views.
   In an interview with the Vietnam News Agency, Thach said that
for the first time, all parties in the conflict agreed that the two
pivotal issues in resolving the conflict were the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops from Cambodia and eliminating danger from the
Khmer Rouge.
   The talks included Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen and
representatives of the resistance, as well as Vietnam, Laos and
representatives of the six-member Association of Southeast Asian
Nations.
   Sihanouk also met last week with representatives of the warring
factions in Jakarta, Indonesia. The prince, who last month resigned
as president of the three-party resistance coalition, did not
attend the peace talks in Bogor.
   He said before departing from Indonesia on Friday that the talks
had been a success.
   But when asked about the prospects for peace after Indonesia, he
said they were ``very slim. That's the reason why I am going to
meet again with Hun Sen'' in Paris in October.
   He said that if the four warring factions, including Hun Sen,
agreed that Vietnam should end its military occupation of Cambodia,
``Vietnam would have no pretext to stay in Cambodia.''
   Vietnam has pledged to withdraw its estimated 120,000 troops by
1990, but has demanded that the Khmer Rouge be disarmed and not
play a role in a future Cambodian government.
   The prince said in his meetings with government official in
Beijing that he would not make any demands on the Chinese, who
supply the Khmer Rouge with military and financial support.
   At the talks in Indonesia, all parties agreed for the need to
put into place a political solution to end a conflict which began
in 1979 following the Vietnamese invasion of Cambodia. Since then,
the three-party resistance, including the Khmer Rouge, has been
fighting Hanoi's forces and the government in Phnom Penh.
   But Thach has opposed proposals for an international armed force
that would disarm the warring factions, including the Khmer Rouge,
who some fear will return to power once Hanoi's forces are
withdrawn.
   ``Only the Cambodian people, victims of the genocidal (Khmer
Rouge) clique, can disarm (them),'' he said in the interview. ``No
foreign force whatever can disarm the Pol Pot force.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 to end the Khmer Rouge's
three years in power, during which they killed hundreds of
thousands of Cambodians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
