<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Rights     07-30 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Rights,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Says Paying Family Of Missing Student Doesn't Acknowledge
Guilt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry said Saturday
that the decision to pay damages to the family of a leftist student
who disappeared while in police custody is not an admission of
guilt.
   It issued a statement saying the payment would be made out of
respect for the Inter-American Court of Human Rights.
   The court on Friday, after eight months of hearings and
deliberations, ruled that Honduras was responsible for the death of
student leader Angel Manfredo Velasquez, 35, and must pay damages
to his family.
   Presidential spokesman Lisando Quesada refused to say how much
the government would pay.
   Two witnesses in the case were shot to death in January and
human human rights groups blamed the killings on rightist death
squads.
   Velasquez was a student at the National University's college of
economics when police arrested him Sept. 8, 1981, during the
military government of Gen. Policapo Paz Garcia.
   He was never seen again.
   Student and labor organizations protested his disappearance.
Several armed groups briefly invaded radio stations, newspapers and
news agencies to demand an investigation.
   The ruling was the first by the court, an Organization of
American States agency. Its seven international jurists are hearing
other cases of Central Americans who disappeared while in police
custody or allegedly suffered human rights abuses.
   The Foriegn Ministery statement said the government did not feel
the evidence produced in the Velasquez trial proved Honduras was
guilty in the disappearance. It said it ``hopes its dignified
example will be an incentive to other nations to adhere to human
rights accords and accept the jurisdiction of the court.''
   Honduras' independent Human Rights Commission says 150 people
have disappeared in Honduras after being picked up by security
forces over the past eight years and about 800 people have been
slain in political killings.
   Amnesty International, the London-based rights organization,
reported in February that death squads linked to the Honduran
military are waging a new campaign of torture and terror against
government opponents.
   Amnesty said arbitrary arrests and torture of prisoners are
widespread.
   Honduras returned to civilian rule in 1982 after a decade of
military governments. But President Jose Azcona Hoyo's civilian
administration remains dependent on the support of the armed forces.
</TEXT>
