<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ExpelledArmenian     07-30 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Expelled Armenian,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Says Soviet Union Had No Right To Expel Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY ZAMPARUTTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Armenian dissident expelled from the Soviet Union
said Saturday that the Soviet Union had no right to expel him or to
deprive him of his citizenship.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan, who arrived Saturday afternoon at Rome's
Leonardo da Vinci Airport, is expected to seek U.S. asylum.
   But he said through a translator that the Soviet Union had no
right ``to deprive me of Armenian citizenship,'' and he would ``try
to return'' to his native land to fight for the rights of Armenians.
   Ayrikyan, 39, arrived by plane from Ethiopia, which had accepted
him after Soviet authorities banished him July 21.
   The Armenian nationalist served 17 years in a Soviet prison
until his release last year after the Kremlin reviewed political
sentencings. But he was jailed again March 25 after he told Western
journalists about the unrest in the Soviet republic of Armenia.
   Soviet authorities banished him after charging him with slander.
   Ayrikyan, wearing a gray suit, was met in Rome by his cousin,
Sylva Ayrikyan, now living in France, and by a representative of
the U.S. Embassy.
   The dissident received a seven-day Italian visa, but ``nothing
is determined'' about his immediate plans, according to a French
lawyer, who spoke on condition of anonymity and said he represented
members of Ayrikyan's family living in France.
   While in Ethiopia, Ayrikyan said his immediate wishes were to
visit his family in France, then head to the United States and
settle in the Los Angeles area.
   Ayrikyan said in Rome that he and other dissidents were fighting
for human rights in the Soviet Union and that he had not violated
any laws.
   The dissident said thousands of Armenians had written letters to
the Soviet government demanding his return.
   Ayrikyan provoked Soviet officials when he provided news to
Western reporters in Moscow about the campaign in the republic of
Armenia to annex the disputed region of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is
part of the neighboring Azerbaijan republic.
   More than three-quarters of the residents of Nagorno-Karabakh
are Armenian.
   Following a harsh speech by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
against ethnic nationalism, the Kremlin said July 18 that the
disputed region will remain in Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
