<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson     07-30 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,440,</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Trail He Blazed Will One Day Lead Blacks To White
House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Saturday his unsuccessful
presidential bid was a victory for America's disenfranchised,
opening the political process and blazing a trail that would lead
one day to a black occupying the White House.
   In his first public appearance since the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta, Jackson told an overflow gathering at
Operation PUSH, the civil-rights organization he helped found,
``Victory is expanding the party and the process. ... Losing is
being locked out.''
   ``What did it mean when my children stood there'' on the DNC
platform? ``It meant that your children stood there too. It means
that in 1992 or 1996, I may or may not get there, but our children
will get there in our lifetime.''
   Jackson called Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis a ``viable
alternative'' to Republican Vice President George Bush, drawing a
hearty ovation when he said, ``Dukakis pledged to not bring shame
to the White House. Bush does not recognize shame at the White
House.''
   He repeated many of the same themes he sounded in his rousing
DNC speech, saying the breadth of his influence could be measured
by the inclusion in the party platform of planks calling for
greater investment in the nation's cities and schools, affordable
housing, and a declaration that South Africa is a ``terrorist
state.''
   ``We are changing both parties. Bush now follows our lead with
his attack on drugs. He has moved away from Mrs. Reagan and the
astrologers and just saying `no.' Now Bush follows our lead with a
budget commitment to day care,'' said Jackson.
   ``Now Bush, with the `sleaze factor' of the Reagan
administration, calls for an ethics committee.''
   Still sounding at times like a candidate, Jackson reminded his
supporters that the momentum built during his campaign, the funds
and issues that were raised and the voters registered, must not be
wasted.
   ``Dukakis or Bush will be our president in 1988. Those choices
will change or expand in our lifetime. We're just an attitude away
from winning the nomination. We have the votes, we're gaining the
experience,'' he said.
   ``The issue will not be who chooses us for the ticket, but it
will be who we choose,'' Jackson added. ``Through hard work, we
will win.''
   ``Politics is not a one-round fight. It is not an even fight.
Sometimes, referees, judges and even the rules are stacked against
you,'' said Jackson. ``You cannot surrender, have a thin skin or a
glass jaw. You have to hang in there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
