<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0585 07-30 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0585,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says Iraqis Pushed to Border, Iraq Says It Withdrew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Iran saying it drove
Iraqis from four towns, Iraq reporting massive air raids and enemy
losses, CORRECTS that Iraqis did not deny chemical bomb report and
Iran sted Iraq saying it pushed Iraqi troops out of Sar-e Pol-e
Zahab, picks up 9th graf pvs, On Friday...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Saturday that its troops drove
Iraqi soldiers occupying four towns back to the border and blunted
a new Iraqi offensive elsewhere. Iraq said it withdrew from
occupied areas.
   The Iraqis seized the western Iranian areas in a week of
fighting that followed Iran's announcement July 18 that it would
accept a cease-fire in the eight-year war.
   In reports monitored in Nicosia, Iran said Iraqi forces
chemically bombed a village just inside the border near the town of
Marivan in northwestern Iran. It reported Iraqi shelling of
villages near Sardasht in the same region.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said 10 civilians
were wounded when chemical bombs were dropped on the village of
Bilo.
   The agency said Iraqi conventional shells wounded 40 civilians
and damaged several houses in 10 villages around Sardasht in the
mountainous northwest.
   Iraq denied shelling Sardasht and made no comment on the
chemical bomb report.
   In its daily military communique in Baghdad, Iraq on Saturday
reported massive air strikes against Iranian positions all along
the warfront.
   The communique said Iraqi jetfighters carried out 125 combat
missions and its helicopter gunships flew 89 sorties, inflicting
``considerable losses on the enemy in men, equipment and weapons.''
   Iran said its forces liberated the towns of Karand, Amirabad,
Qasr-e Shirin and Sar-e Pol-e Zahab in the central front, pushing
Iraqi troops back to the border.
   But a military spokesman, quoted by the official Iraqi News
Agency, said Iraqi forces had pulled out of the towns it occupied
in the central front. The spokesman said Iraqi forces had pulled
out of Qasr-e Shirin, Sumar and Amirabad.
   Tehran radio, also monitored in Cyprus, said Iraqi forces
launched an attack a little farther south, around the town of
Mehran on the south-central war front. It said they were pushed
back.
   ``A heavy battle is raging in the area and our Moslem combatants
have forced the Iraqis to retreat,'' the radio said.
   On Friday, Hashemi Rafsanjani, Iran's acting commander in chief,
said Iraqi forces and Iranian rebels advanced 65 miles into Iran
before Iran pushed them back toward the border.
   Speaking at a prayer service broadcast Friday on Tehran radio,
Rafsanjani said Iraqi-backed Iranian rebels had entered a hospital
in the western town of Eslamabad and ``rained bullets on some 30
patients,'' killing all of them.
   Iran said it drove the rebel fighters out of Eslamabad and
Karand, 60 miles inside Iran, killing or wounding 4,500 invaders in
a ``heavy battle'' against ``forces of the Baghdad regime and their
hypocritical mercenaries.''
   Iranian news reports, monitored in Nicosia, said more than 1,000
Iraqi tanks and personnel carriers were either destroyed or seized
in the fighting. ``The operation destroyed the Islamic republic's
cancer, which ... could have caused problems for Iranians,''
Rafsanjani told the prayer congregation in Tehran in an apparent
reference to the rebels.
   The rebel group, in a communique released in Baghdad, said its
fighters returned to their bases Friday after killing or wounding
40,000 Iranian Revolutionary Guards in three days of fighting.
   No independent observers were allowed near the fighting and
claims from both sides could not be verified.
</TEXT>
