<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-30 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Move Into The Lower Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Saturday around the lower Great Lakes
and over parts of the South, sections of Missouri got heavy rain,
and record heat returned to the Northeast.
   By early afternoon, thunderstorms extended around the lakes from
southeastern Wisconsin and southern Lower Michigan across western
New York state and the Ohio Valley.
   Wind gusted to about 60 mph over Lake Erie and to 70 mph near
Dansville, N.Y. Wind and hail damaged trees in parts of Ohio and
western New York, the National Weather Service said.
   Thunderstorms also developed over the Tennessee Valley, Georgia,
Alabama, Florida and the Gulf of Mexico coast.
   Wind gusts during storms damaged power lines and telephone lines
near Swansea, S.C., the weather service said.
   In Missouri, thunderstorms from Friday evening into Saturday
morning left 3.20 inches of rain at Kearney, 2.68 inches at
Richmond and 2.65 inches at Lexington.
   Showers also were scattered over north-central New Mexico,
southwestern Arizona and southeastern California.
   Temperatures climbed higher than normal across the Northeast and
Baltimore hit a record 102 downtown. Other records were 92 at
Bridgeport, Conn.; 98 at Hartford, Conn.; and Philadelphia tied its
record of 98.
   Elsewhere, Lander, Wyo., hit a record high of 96.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 61
degrees at Port Angeles, Wash., and San Simeon, Calif., to 103 at
Rapid City, S.D. The low Saturday morning was 42 degrees at
Jackson, Wyo.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from New
England across the Appalachians, over Florida, along the Texas Gulf
Coast, and from the southern Rockies across Arizona.
   Highs near 80 or in the 80s were predicted in northern New
England and much of the Great Lakes, scattered over the southern
Rockies into northern Arizona, and along the Pacific Coast; around
100 from central Texas across central Kansas, as well as over the
Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah; near 110 across the desert
Southwest; and in the 90s or near 90 in the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
