<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmallTownRiot     07-30 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Town Riot,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Curfew Lifted Two Days After Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNBURY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Town Council on Saturday lifted an
emergency curfew imposed after the young people rioted and marched
on the police station to protest underage drinking arrests, the
mayor said.
   Mayor Charles Moll ordered a dusk-to-dawn curfew for groups on
the streets after about 50 young people smashed windows and marched
on the police station Thursday night. He also asked the
Pennsylvania National Guard to be ready if police were unable to
control the crowd.
   ``We hope that everything is going back to normal,'' Moll said.
``We felt the emergency was over. We'll have to see what happens.''
   Thursday's disturbance in this north-central Pennsylvania town
of 1,300 was seen by some as the culmination of months of tension
between police and young people who gather on the town's main
thoroughfare.
   ``All they want to do is loaf on the main street,'' Moll said
after the riot. ``There's drugs, there's drink, there's sex.''
   Tensions flared late Thursday when officers attempted to arrest
a 17-year-old girl and an 18-year-old man for drinking and they
resisted arrest, police said.
   Six people were charged with participating in a riot.
</TEXT>
