<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party     07-30 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Sets Deadlines for Implementing Gorbachev's
Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party set deadlines for overhauling
the party, government and judiciary to speed Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reform program, according to resolutions announced Saturday by Tass.
   The resolutions involve key issues the 57-year-old Soviet leader
outlined in a speech Friday at a one-day meeting of the 300-plus
member party Central Committee.
   Tass, the official news agency, reported the Central Committee
resolutions, passed after Gorbachev's speech, commit the party and
government to the timetable Gorbachev had sought.
   The first deadline is October when a draft law on amendments to
the constitution and on multi-candidate elections of legislators is
to be finished. The Supreme Soviet, or parliament, will then review
the proposals.
   By year's end, the 20-million-member party is to have
reorganized, pruning itself to include only ``politically mature,
well-prepared Communists possessing high moral qualities and
capable of organizing work in a new way.''
   Gorbachev, the party's general secretary, told the Central
Committee Friday, ``I want to repeat again and again, comrades,
that the time of vigorous action has come and we must not tarry.''
   He said the reorganized party ``should be totally relieved of
administrative-managerial functions and concentrate its work on the
key directions of home and foreign policy and shift the center of
gravity to political methods of guidance.''
   Tass reported these other timetables:
   Elections are to be held in March for 2,250 representatives to a
new body, the Congress of Peoples' Deputies, that will meet the
following month. The first business of the Congress will be to vote
for a new parliament of at least 400 members and for a Soviet
president.
   The new parliament is to draft laws promised long ago on the
rights of youths and trade unions and the role of the press,
according to the resolutions as reported by Tass.
   In the party, the ruling Politburo is to complete by early 1989
proposals on an explosive issue in Soviet society _ relations among
the country's more than 100 nationalities. The proposals will then
go before the policy-making Central Committee for a session on
ethnic relations.
   By the middle of l989, a revamping of the roles of judges,
prosecutors, lawyers and investigators is to be completed.
Gorbachev, a law school graduate, has said the legal system must be
improved to prevent a repeat of the repression suffered under
former Soviet leader Josef Stalin and the corruption that existed
under the leadership of Leonid I. Brezhnev.
</TEXT>
