<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1842EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     07-30 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contract Talks Collapse, Strikers Plan To Picket `Roger Rabbit'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIC LEYVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract talks between scriptwriters and
movie and television producers collapsed Saturday, erasing earlier
optimism that weekend talks might end the 21-week-old,
industry-crippling strike.
   Striking scriptwriters immediately pledged to picket theaters
showing the hit film ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' a move to target
Walt Disney Studios.
   Representatives from the Writers Guild of America and the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers left the
bargaining table in the early morning hours Saturday without a
settlement in the strike, which has halted most Hollywood
production.
   Federal mediator Floyd Wood declared the meetings adjourned,
calling negotiations deadlocked.
   Guild writers scheduled informational picketing Sunday at two of
the largest theaters in Los Angeles, said union spokeswoman Cheryl
Rhoden.
   ``We'll take our message to the public,'' Ms. Rhoden said. ``And
we're targeting `Roger Rabbit' because it's a Disney venture and
Disney has maintained a continuous hard-line position.''
   The producers planned a Sunday news conference, spokesman Herb
Steinberg said.
   Guild officials said they hoped the mediator can get both sides
back to the bargaining table soon, but Steinberg said the
mediator's efforts failed and producers will go ahead with
preparations for a fall television season with whatever writers are
available.
   ``There are no new plans for any further meetings or
discussions, formal, informal, or otherwise,'' Steinberg said.
``Things aren't looking good for a settlement any time soon.''
   Negotiators deadlocked on several issues, with domestic and
foreign television rerun payments topping the list, Ms. Rhoden
said. Steinberg said contention over rerun money from foreign
broadcasts plagued the talks.
   The strike began when more than 9,000 guild members walked off
the job March 7. Despite some internal dissension, the union
rank-and-file has overwhelmingly rejected each contract proposal
offered by producers.
   With the fall TV network schedules in a shambles, producers say
they will reshoot old scripts from canceled shows, using new actors.
   The latest week-long round of talks was held at alliance offices
in Sherman Oaks, about 10 miles north of downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
