<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iran     07-30 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Hopes for Better Relations with Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher told the brother
of captive church envoy Terry Waite, in a letter released Saturday,
that she wants Britain to build on recent hopeful signs in its
relations with Iran.
   However, the Conservative leader also said Britain should make
no concessions for release of hostages.
   She made the comments in a letter to David Waite, dated July 27.
It was released by Lambeth Palace in London, the headquarters of
Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie.
   The Church of England leader sent Terry Waite to Lebanon to seek
release of American hostages held there, but the Anglican envoy
disappeared Jan. 20, 1987. He is believed held by pro-Iranian
Shiite extremists.
   In her letter, the prime minister welcomed Iran's July 18
decision to accept a cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   She added: ``I hope that we can now work together to remove the
obstacles to a better relationship.''
   Britain has limited diplomatic relations with Tehran, with no
British diplomats stationed in the Iranian capital.
   ``Hostage-taking is a crime and anyone with influence over
hostage-takers should use this to help secure their release,'' she
said. ``If the Iranian government is in a position to exert
influence towards this humanitarian objective, we look to it to do
so.''
   The prime minister added: ``I know you agree that the government
should not make concessions to secure the release of hostages, and
I respect your view all the more against the background of distress
which you and your family continue to suffer.''
   David Waite said he welcomed the letter. He said Saturday on
behalf of the Waite family: ``Of course there are problems to be
solved between Britain and Iran. But Mrs. Thatcher's assurance that
good will will be reciprocated is very good news.''
   Kidnappers are believed to hold 18 Westerners, including 9
Americans, hostage in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Saturday in Manama, Bahrain, Mrs. Thatcher said Britain was
prepared to call for a meeting of the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council to help bring peace to the Persian Gulf.
   The prime minister was on a 12-day trip that will include stops
in Singapore, Malaysia, Thailand and Australia.
</TEXT>
