<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ireland-Population,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish Population Drops For First Time In 27 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland's population has dropped for the
first time in 27 years because of mass emigration by young people
seeking work abroad, the government's Central Statistics Office
reported Saturday.
   Ireland's population is estimated to be 3,538,000, or 5,000
fewer people than in April 1987, the office said.
   ``The reason for the net decline in population is emigration,''
it said in a statement.
   Ireland, beset by high taxes and 17 percent unemployment, has
experienced its biggest wave of emigration since the 1920s. An
estimated 25,000 to 30,000 people leave each year.
   The government estimates about 40,000 to 50,000 young Irish have
gone to the United States in the past seven years in search of
better conditions, many as illegal aliens.
</TEXT>
