<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Pemex     07-30 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Pemex,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Pemex Chief Freed After 5 Years in Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government oil company chief who became a
symbol of the corruption of the high-rolling oil boom years was
freed from prison Saturday after serving five years for fraud.
   Mariachi music and scores of supporters, many in tears, greeted
Jorge Diaz Serrano when he walked out the gates of the Southern
Penitentiary arm-in-arm with his wife and flanked by his children
and lawyers.
   A circuit court in March reduced his 10-year sentence to five,
saying the 67-year-old former Pemex chief was smart, capable and
posed no danger to society. The Supreme Court upheld the reduced
sentence July 18.
   Diaz Serrano, an ex-senator, proclaimed his innocence Saturday,
as he has from the outset. He told reporters he planned to devote
himself to business and politics.
   ``I am returning to freedom, but not because there has been
justice,'' he said.
   President Miguel de la Madrid made the cases of Diaz Serrano and
former Mexico City police chief Arturo Durazo Moreno centerpieces
of his ``moral renovation'' campaign in the early 1980s.
   With the de la Madrid administration winding to a close, the
extortion case against the former police chief is still pending.
   Diaz Serrano was convicted in 1983 of embezzling $34 million
from Pemex through a gas tanker deal.
   In the 1980 deal, a Liberian-based firm, Navigas International,
bought two natural gas tankers from the Belgian shipbuilder
Boelwerf for $124 million. It then immediately sold them to Pemex
for $158 million.
   Diaz Serrano was convicted of pocketing the difference.
   He was sentenced to 10 years in prison and fined the equivalent
of $58 million.
   Diaz Serrano headed the government oil company from 1976 to
1981, the oil boom years of former President Jose Lopez Portillo.
   After leaving Pemex, Diaz Serrano was elected senator from the
northern state of Sonora. Congress later stripped him of
legislative immunity from prosecution.
   Defense lawyer Enrique Mendoza Morales said Diaz Serrano cannot
pay the $58 million fine but cannot be held in prison under Mexican
law for that reason.
   Mendoza Morales said the government has confiscated about a $1
million in assets from Diaz Serrano, including property in the
resort cities of Cuernavaca and Acapulco and an art collection.
   A minor charge of criminal association is still pending against
Diaz Serrano, who paid $4,350 bail to get out of prison, his lawyer
said.
</TEXT>
