<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BickeringBelugas     07-30 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bickering Belugas,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Aquarium Belugas Bitten In Bickering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just five days after they were returned to the
National Aquarium after a year elsewhere, three beluga whales got
into some bloody bickering that left two of them with bites and
scrapes.
   Aquarium officials say fighting isn't out of the ordinary for
the species, but these three whales had never fought before
Friday's tiff.
   The three whales had been living together harmoniously for
nearly a year at the New York Aquarium while the Baltimore
aquarium's 260,000-gallon tank underwent a $1 million renovation.
   ``I don't think the move had anything to do with it,'' said Bob
Jenkins, director of operations and husbandry at the aquarium.
   Kia, the youngest whale, was found to have been bitten on the
tail.
   Possibly Kia had been following the other two, Anore and
Illamar, around the tank and one of them turned around and bit her,
Jenkins suggested.
   ``Or maybe they just got up on the wrong side of the tank,'' he
said.
   Then 6-year-old Anore suffered scrapes, probably while keepers
were trying to herd the marine mammals into a shallow area of the
tank.
   Jenkins compared the severity of the wounds with ``your
5-year-old kid with a knee scrape.''
   Aquarium staffers treated the whales' wounds with gauze and
disinfectant.
   ``There will be a little bit of concern of what to do if the
fighting continues,'' he said.
   Anore and Illamar were captured in Hudson Bay in 1985.
</TEXT>
