<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Guyana-Festival     07-30 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guyana-Festival,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 130 Artists Attend Abolition Celebrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 130 singers, dancers,
musicians and actors from a dozen countries are participating in
celebrations marking the 150th anniversary of the end of slavery in
this former British colony.
   Billed as the biggest cultural event since the Caribbean Arts
Festival was staged in Guyana in 1972, artists began three weeks of
performances Friday night.
   After the visiting artists take part in a daylong folk festival
Monday in Georgetown, they will fan out to the rest of this South
American nation of 825,000.
   Twenty-five scholars from Africa, Latin America, the Caribbean
and United States are also holding a three-day conference, entitled
``Genesis of a Nation,'' which ends Sunday. Among the topics
discussed were the impact of African culture on Guyana and the
effect of slavery on the country's black population.
   About 40 percent of Guyanese are black. Most other Guyanese are
of East Indian stock, descendents of indentured servants brought to
this former sugar producing colony after the abolition of slavery
in 1833.
   Friday night's festivities were marked by a power blackout
during the opening show in Georgetown's National Park. President
Desmond Hoyte was among those in the audience when the lights went
out.
   The government set aside a $400,000 budget for the celebrations,
which feature delegations from Nigeria, Venezuela, Suriname,
Jamaica, United States, Britain and several Caribbean island-states.
   Among the participants are South Africa's U.S.-based singer
Miriam Makeba and two calypso singers _ the Mighty Sparrow and the
Mighty Gabby _ of Barbados.
</TEXT>
