<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FirstRepublicBank     07-30 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-First RepublicBank,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Struggling Bank Reopens With New Owners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bank Rescues, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas' largest bank opened Saturday under new
ownership, a North Carolina corporation whose chairman saluted
Dallas billionaire H. Ross Perot for helping seal the deal to take
over the crippled bank.
   NCNB Corp. of Charlotte, N.C., acquired First RepublicBank on
Friday in what may evolve into a $4 billion federal rescue, the
largest in banking history. The new bank opened Saturday as NCNB
Texas National Bank.
   ``We believe Mr. Perot's willingness to step forward as an
investor was very important,'' NCNB Chairman Hugh L. McColl Jr.
said Saturday.
   Perot emerged as a key player in the deal when he told the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. that, if needed, he would back
NCNB's venture, tabbed at between $210 million and $240 million.
   ``I agreed to underwrite it, which was an insignificant public
service to the people of Texas because NCNB, without even breaking
a bead of perspiration, can raise well over $200 million,'' said
Perot, who attended a news conference Saturday with NCNB officers.
   The FDIC approved the takeover by NCNB of the Dallas-based First
RepublicBank, which has been struggling since a downturn in the
state's economy. It had posted a loss of nearly $2.3 billion in the
first six months of 1988.
   Timothy P. Hartman, NCNB's chief financial officer, said the
bank probably would finance the deal through the sale of
securities. Under the agreement, NCNB takes control of 20 percent
of the equity of the new bank and 100 percent of the voting common
stock.
   The bank will be split into two divisions to separate operating
bank assets, valued at an estimated $20 billion, and a special
asset pool of troubled assets of about $5 billion, Hartman said.
   The FDIC will absorb costs in resolving the bad assets, he said.
   NCNB officers expressed confidence in the Texas economy despite
depressions in oil, real estate and financial services sectors.
   McColl said the move will give NCNB investors a presence in a
major market with a manageable risk, saying that the economy has
bottomed out in Texas and most signposts in the economy point
toward a steady recovery.
   ``This is a new bank and it's up and running,'' said Francis B.
``Buddy'' Kemp, NCNB president and chairman of NCNB Texas National.
   Kemp said he foresaw no layoffs or management upheavals in the
takeover. The bank has 12,200 employees and 134 banking locations
in the state.
</TEXT>
