<2ND_LINE>AM-Stranded Kids,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Soccer Team Stranded In Miami En Route To Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NAN HERLIHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oklahoma boys soccer team en route to a
Brazilian tournament has been stranded in Miami since Thursday, and
Saturday the youngsters set up camp at the airport until they can
board a flight.
   ``This is a nightmare _ a horror movie that travels with
children,'' said Robert L. Daniels, a parent escorting the players,
ages 11 through 15.
   A Pan American World Airways spokesman said Saturday the group
should be on a flight to Brazil no later than Sunday, giving them a
chance to play in five games. The youngsters said they already have
missed several practices and at least one game that was to be
nationally televised in Brazil.
   ``Miami is exciting, sort of,'' said bleary-eyed Rusty Green,
11, of Edmond, Okla. ``But I wish I was in Brazil now. I'm a pretty
good soccer player.''
   The soccer group of about 100 adults and children left Oklahoma
on Thursday, but Pan Am was unable to seat 15 adults and 36
children on the final leg of their trip to Brazil, a flight from
Miami to Sao Paulo.
   Alan Loflin, a Pan Am spokesman in Miami, blamed a high volume
of travelers for the delay. ``This is peak season crunch time,'' he
said. The parents said the group had confirmed tickets, but Loflin
could not verify that.
   Loflin said an extra Boeing 747 non-stop flight to Sao Paulo was
added for Sunday to accommodate the soccer group and other delayed
passengers.
   ``I'm confident we can get them out Sunday at the latest,'' he
said.
   After the soccer entourage was bumped from its flight Thursday,
the group checked into a nearby hotel where rooms are $77 per
night. Daniels said Pan Am would not pay the bill. The group
couldn't get on a flight Friday, either.
   So, rather than watch the boys' spending money ``disappear like
water through a faucet'' on hotel bills and meals, the chaperones
decided Saturday afternoon to check out and set up housekeeping at
the airport.
   ``In the halls, I guess,'' Daniels said as he herded the team
onto an airport shuttle bus.
   Daniels said the boys' disappointment grows each night they
don't leave.
   ``They're bawling and crying and we have kids calling their
parents at 1 a.m. upset,'' Daniels said.
   ``This trip is a big deal to these kids,'' said Kay Green, a
parent from Clinton, Okla. She said the soccer players ``drove
combines and washed cars and did anything'' to raise $1,500 each
for the trip.
</TEXT>
