<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increase Reported in Ethiopian War Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government newspaper reported
Saturday that the number of refugees from civil war in Eritrea has
grown over the past six weeks from 6,000 to 80,000.
   The increase comes as government troops are stepping up their
campaign against separatist guerrillas in Eritrea and Tigre,
Ethiopia's northernmost regions. The government banned foreign
relief workers from the area in April, complaining that insurgents
were intercepting their shipments.
   Refugees in Eritrea are living in tents and makeshift shelters
mainly near the towns of Asmara, Keren, Eleberid, Ghinda and
Massawa, according to the weekly Yezarietu Ethiopia.
   The fighting in neighboring Tigre has created another 7,300
refugees, the report said.
   The newspaper said the displaced people in Tigre are living in
makeshift shelters near Mekelle. They have trekked from surrounding
areas in search of food and other help, the newspaper said.
   It said emergency assistance was being provided to 2.6 million
people in both regions.
   More than 12,000 tons of grain and supplementary food was
provided to slightly more than one million Eritreans in June
through 30 distribution centers, the government's Relief and
Rehabilitation Commission was quoted as saying.
   The newspaper said that from March to June about 127,000 tons of
grain and supplementary food and blankets were distributed to 1.5
million people in Tigre.
   The government has been battling insurgents in Eritrea for 27
years and in Tigre for 14 years. It officially acknowledged the
civil wars for the first time in March.
   Millions of Ethiopians driven by drought and civil war have also
fled into neighboring Somalia and Sudan. The government in Sudan,
meanwhile, is fighting its own war, and thousands of Sudanese
refugees have fled into Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
