<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Hurley     07-30 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hurley,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nutrition Scholar Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucille S. Hurley Thompson, a
nutrition scholar whose research linked some dietary deficiencies
of expectant mothers with birth defects, has died at age 66.
   The University of California, Davis, professor died Thursday
morning in a Sacramento hospital after open-heart surgery.
   Beginning in the 1950s, she studied the effects of the trace
metals manganese, zinc, magnesium, iron and copper on fetal
development.
   During her career, she received two Guggenheim Fellowships, five
visiting scholar appointments abroad and numerous nutrition
research awards. She served on several committees of the National
Institutes of Health and the National Academy of Sciences national
research council.
   She was named editor of the Journal of Nutrition in 1984 and had
served as president of three national scientific organizations.
   Known professionally as Dr. Hurley, she was born in Riga,
Latvia, now part of the Soviet Union, and immigrated to the United
States with her family at age 3.
   She is survived by her husband, Kenneth Thompson of Sacramento;
a daughter, Barbara Jungerman of San Francisco; a son, Michael
Hurley of Shingle Springs; a stepdaughter, Tamara Wright of
Seattle; stepsons, Nicolas Thompson of West Sacramento and Marcus
Thompson of San Jose; a brother, Dr. Milton Shapson of Milwaukee; a
sister, Phyllis Shapson of Los Angeles; and two grandsons.
</TEXT>
