<HEAD>Fog Blamed For Traffic Accidents That Kill 13</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0638 to RESTORE slugline</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thick fog blanketed sections of the
main highway linking Sao Paulo with Rio de Janeiro and police said
it caused three chain accidents early Saturday in which 13 people
were killed and 45 injured.
   The accidents involved dozes of cars, trucks and buses and were
near the town of Jacarei, 48 miles north of Sao Paulo, according to
highway patrolman Joao Goncalves.
   He gave this account:
   Six people were killed, including four from one family, in an
accident involving at least 25 vehicles.
   Two miles away a truck driver was killed in a five-vehicle
pileup.
   Six people perished when four cars were engulfed in flames in an
accident involving two trucks and five cars.
   Goncalves said fog covered most of the Paraiba valley early
Saturday and turned several miles of the busy Dutra highway
connecting two of Brazil's main cities into ``a deadly trap.''
   ``You could't see more than a few yards away, '' he said.
</TEXT>
