<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Military     07-30 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Military,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China to Restore Military Ranks Aug. 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China announced Saturday it was restoring a
military rank system abolished by Mao Tse-tung 23 years ago as part
of his attempt to turn China into a classless society.
   The official Xihnua News Agency said more than 100,000 military
officers will wear their uniforms on Monday, which is Army Day, and
join a new civilian staff of scientists, teachers and other
specialists.
   Also Saturday, a ceremony was held reviving the bestowing of
medals to the military. Communist Party General Secretary Zhao
Ziyang, President Yang Shangkun and Premier Li Peng attended the
ceremony at the Great Hall of the People, in which more than 80,000
military veterans received medals.
   The military reforms are the work of Deng Xiaoping, Mao's
successor as China's top leader and head of the Central Military
Commission. Deng was not present at Saturday's ceremony.
   Deng, 84, has abandoned Mao's concept of a massive peasant army
and sought to turn the People's Liberation Army into a streamlined,
well-equipped and modern fighting force.
   In the past few years he has reduced the world's largest army
from 4 million to 3 million, concentrated on developing modern
weapons systems and pushed for the reinstatement of ranks.
   The restoration of ranks and the awarding of medals, banned by
Mao in 1965, is an effort to boost army morale when the military
has been overshadowed in China's push for economic modernization.
   Under the reforms, military officers in the army are to be
divided into three grades with 11 ranks. There will be four ranks
of generals, four ranks of field officer _ senior colonel, colonel,
lieutenant colonel and major _ and three ranks of company officer _
captain, lieutenant and second lieutenant.
</TEXT>
