<2ND_LINE>AM-Crop-dusters Collide,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop-Duster Planes Collide, Pilots Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS age of Tiefenback to 63 sted 53 in 3rd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALMYRA, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crop-duster aircraft clipped the tail
section of another crop-duster, causing the planes to crash into a
soybean field and killing the two pilots, officials said Saturday.
   The single-engine, propeller-driven aircraft crashed Friday
night into a farm adjacent to the Almyra Municipal Airport, about
60 miles southeast of Little Rock. The veteran pilots were
finishing up spraying insecticide on soybean fields when the
accident occurred.
   The pilots were identified as James R. Perry, 35, and George W.
Tiefenback Jr., 63, both of Almyra.
   Debbie Dowdy, a radio operator with the Arkansas State Police,
said Perry had just turned off his sprayer when his plane clipped
the tail section of Tiefenback's aircraft.
   State Police Trooper Barry Roy said the planes had been going
back and forth between the airport and the field. He speculated
that the pilots got out of sequence and were unaware they were both
over the field.
   A Federal Aviation Administration investigator was at the crash
scene Saturday and could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
