<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviets-Germany     07-30 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Germany,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Concerned About West European Moves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev expressed concern
Saturday to West Germany's foreign minister about Western European
plans for greater military and economic integration, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said Gorbachev told Hans-Dietrich
Genscher at a meeting in the Kremlin that the plans could set back
progress for disarmament and security in Europe.
   It reported Gorbachev said West European politicians must bear
responsibility for any damage to ``positive beginnings'' toward
improving security.
   Genscher told Gorbachev that the creation of a single market by
1992 within the 12-member European Economic Community would not
endanger the continent and ``increases possibilities for
cooperation and openness,'' according to the Tass report.
   Genscher arrived in Moscow Friday and is to prepare for the
October visit to the Soviet capital by West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl. Gorbachev is to visit West Germany during the first
half of 1989.
   Tass said that Gorbachev, referring to international
negotiations in Vienna on reducing conventional arms in Europe,
told Genscher ``no one should count on our unilateral
disarmament.'' The North Atlantic Treaty Organization contends that
the Soviet Union has larger conventional forces there and should
make bigger cuts.
   Genscher told reporters after the meeting that he and Gorbachev
discussed ways to speed efforts to agree on reducing conventional
weapons in Europe.
</TEXT>
