<HEAD>2,000 March in Funeral Procession For Leftist Leader</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto SAL1</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 people marched
through the capital Saturday to mourn a leftist leader whose death
has been blamed by associates on government security forces.
   Hundreds of helmeted riot police with clubs and assault rifles
kept watch, but there were no reports of violence.
   Marchers in Saturday's procession carried the coffin of
Rigoberto Orellana, whose battered body was found at a downtown
street on Thursday.
   Orellana was one of the founders of a 6-week-old movement known
as Bread, Labor, Work and Liberty, a leftist alliance of unionists,
peasants and students.
   Alliance leaders said Friday that a car driven by a member of
the government security forces had hit him intentionally.
   However, speakers at Saturday's march said he had been beaten to
death. They said Orellana's body was dumped at the curb to make his
death look like a hit-and-run accident.
   The Associated Press was unable to locate anyone who would
comment on the murder accusation in repeated telephone calls to the
armed forces press office Friday and Saturday.
   Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Vides Casanova has called the new
leftist group a front for the leftist guerrillas who have fought
the U.S.-backed government for eight years.
   On Friday, about 600 marchers demonstrated in memorial to at
least 14 students who were shot by security forces trying to
disperse a protest on July 30, 1975.
</TEXT>
