<HEAD>Two Suspects Held Pending U.S. Extradition Request</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men wanted in connection with a drug
syndicate that allegedly attempted to smuggle heroin to the United
States in the bodies of dead fish were jailed Saturday pending a
U.S. extradition request, police said.
   Police spokesman Robert Yiu identified the two suspects as Wong
Tsz-keung, a 34-year-old Chinese-American, and Leung Tak-lun, a
37-year-old Hong Kong factory owner.
   The two were arrested Friday at their homes in the British
colony. Yiu said they appeared in court Saturday and were remanded
in jail custody for 45 days pending the arrival of extradition
documents from the United States.
   Police said the two men were members of a syndicate broken March
9 when police in the Chinese city of Shanghai found a large number
of dead fish among 25 boxes of fish scheduled to be shipped to San
Francisco aboard a Chinese airliner.
   Authorities found sutures in the sides of the dead fish and 7.8
pounds of heroin packets planted inside.
   Eleven people _ six in China, three in the United States and two
in Hong Kong _ were arrested following the seizure.
