<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Angola     07-30 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Angola,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Government Gives Sanctuary to Woman In Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Embassy in Angola has given refuge to
a woman who reportedly was detained for two years by the African
National Congress, the Foreign Office said Saturday.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, who was not named in keeping with
British custom, said the British government was trying to obtain an
exit visa for Olivia Forsyth. She has dual South African-British
nationality, the domestic agency Press Association reported.
   ``She has sought refuge there (in the embassy in the Angolan
capital of Luanda), having been detained against her will by the
ANC for 22 months,'' said the spokesman.
   ``She has asked to be allowed to come back to Britain and we are
asking the Angolans to give her an exit visa.''
   The Mail on Sunday newspaper reported that Miss Forsyth, 27, was
closely involved with black opposition groups in South Africa,
including the ANC, which is outlawed in South Africa.
   The newspaper reported that it was believed that she was held at
an ANC prison near Lubango, southern Angola, because she was
accused of spying for the South African secret service.
   It reported that she had been staying at the British Embassy in
Luanda for nearly 10 weeks.
   The ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, made no immediate comment.
   The ANC says its goals, which it now believes can only be
achieved by the overthrow of South Africa's white-led government,
are for a one-man, one-vote state.
   Under South Africa's system of apartheid, the 26 million black
majority has no vote in national affairs, and the 5 million whites
control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and
health services.
</TEXT>
