<HEAD>Government Posts Reward to Help Solve Solidarity Adviser's Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has offered an $11,000
reward in an effort to solve the killing of an adviser to the
banned Solidarity labor movement, the state-run news agency said
Saturday.
   The announcement of the Interior Ministry reward came two weeks
after more than 1,000 mourners, including Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa, attended Jan Strzelecki's funeral in a Warsaw cemetery. The
inquiry into the slaying has become a major area of concern for
Polish intellectuals and senior Solidarity advisers.
   Police found the body of Strzelecki, an opposition sociologist,
near the Vistula River on June 30, the state-run news agency PAP
reported in early July. The sociologist had been dragged from his
car, beaten and thrown down an embankment, according to police.
   Strzelecki remained in a coma until he died from his head
injuries on July 11, a fellow sociologist said at the time.
   PAP said Saturday the Interior Ministry was offering the reward
for information leading to the arrest of those responsible for the
fatal attack.
   A group of Warsaw sociologists on July 6 offered a $2,200 reward
in the case. Polish television Tuesday broadcast a re-enactment of
the crime and broadcast police appeals for help in solving it.
   Solidarity leaders, who say they are puzzled by the case, have
made no public statement about it.
