<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-ContraAid 3rdLd-Writethru a0631 07-30 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Contra Aid, 3rdLd-Writethru, a0631,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Congress to Support Aid to Contras</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: DELETES extra words in 12th graf bgng ``He then...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan renewed his plea for
congressional support of rebels in Nicaragua Saturday and linked a
top official of the country's leftist government with the illicit
drug trade.
   ``While the cutoff of aid to the Freedom Fighters was a dreadful
mistake, getting the cause of peace and freedom back on track, not
recrimination, must now be our goal,'' Reagan said in his weekly
radio address.
   ``There is a chance for a real bipartisan consensus in support
of Contra aid,'' the president said from the presidential retreat
at Camp David.
   He noted that ``one of its strong supporters'' _ Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas, who has voted for aid for the rebels in the past
_ has been named as the Democratic candidate for vice president.
   Reagan appealed for support of legislation being proposed by
Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., that calls for $27 million
in humanitarian assistance, with an additional $20 million in
military aid to be triggered later if it is found to be needed.
   ``Final details are being worked out,'' Reagan said. ``I urge
members of the Senate to support the aid package, and I also ask
the House of Representatives to move speedily and favorably on the
Senate legislation.''
   Reagan said the House decision in February to cut off Contra aid
``removed the principal prod, the military victories and popular
success of the Freedom Fighters, to Sandinista participation in the
peace plan.''
   He said it ``sent an immediate signal of American weakness to
the Communists'' and has had ``costly and sad consequences.''
   ``In Nicaragua, a renewed attack on political dissent is being
led by the head of the secret police, Tomas Borge, a dedicated
Communist and grim, hardened represser of human rights, whose
office, according to our Commission on Organized Crime, has also
been actively engaged in the international drug trade,'' he said.
   ``Acting under the orders of the Communist leaders and Borges'
supervision, Sandinista police and goon squads have brutally broken
up a peaceful demonstration by 3,000 Nicaraguans'' and otherwise
acted against political and religious freedoms, Reagan said.
   In the Democratic response, Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., praised
the congressionally approved drought legislation as ``an important
first step in addressing a situation that threatens America's
farmers.''
   He then said bills approved by Congress concerning defense
spending and plant closings ``deserved the president's support and
which Congress should pass over any presidential veto.''
   On the defense bill, Levin said Congress had given the president
the funding he had requested.
   ``As in the past, President Reagan overemphasized nuclear
weapons and Star Wars at the expense of our conventional weapons,''
the senator said. ``He also proposed actions which would make
effective arms control harder to achieve and maintain.''
   Levin also urged the president to support the plant closing
legislation which requires employers to give workers a 60-day
notice prior to layoffs.
   ``This bill isn't aimed at companies that are going to do the
decent thing anyway,''he said countering the president's argument
against the bill. ``It is aimed at companies, like the one I know
in Michigan, that told its workers on a Friday afternoon that they
were being laid off for two weeks.''
</TEXT>
