<HEAD>Democrats Pick Lieberman To Run Against Weicker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut Democrats nominated state
Attorney General Joseph I. Lieberman for the U.S. Senate Saturday
to challenge three-term Republican Lowell P. Weicker Jr.
   Lieberman did not attend the Democratic State Convention because
it fell on the Jewish Sabbath, and he is an Orthodox Jew. In an
acceptance speech videotaped last week and shown to the 1,305
delegates he said, ``This is not an easy day for me to miss.''
   Lieberman said he was an unworried underdog.
   ``As attorney general, I've fought the big guys against the
odds, time and time again and we've won there,'' he said. ``So long
as I believe in myself and I know that you are with me, together we
can make a difference.''
   Although well behind Weicker in polls, Lieberman has raised $1.3
million to Weicker's $1.8 million, according to the most recent
campaign finance filings.
   Lieberman, the attorney general for six years, was nominated by
acclamation, touching off an eight-minute demonstration led by
gospel singers and Gov. William A. O'Neill doing a lively two-step
on the stage to the delight of onlookers.
   O'Neill and Lieberman have had occasional political skirmishes
over the years. For many years, Lieberman said he would one day
like to be governor. But Lieberman has more recently said he would
not run against O'Neill. The governor has strongly indicated he
will run for a third full term in 1990.
   Referring to Lieberman's ``people's lawyer'' reputation, O'Neill
said: ``You can see the results of his work everywhere you look _
in lower utility rates, in lower grocery prices, in clean rivers
and in pure drinking water.''
   Lieberman, a former state senator from New Haven, criticized
Weicker for his maverick ways, quoting a voter who told him that
Weicker ``has made a lot of noise but he hasn't made a lot of
difference.''
   Lieberman has said during the campaign that his beliefs would
not preclude him from attending Senate sessions on Saturdays should
he be elected, because he would then be performing a service for
others, something permitted in his religion.
</TEXT>
