<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Drake     07-30 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Drake,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed Steel Guitarist, Producer Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grammy Award-winning musician and record
producer Pete Drake, who introduced the ``talking'' steel guitar
style, has died from complications of lung disease. He was 55.
   Drake, who died Friday at his home in suburban Brentwood,
received the Master Award from the Nashville Entertainment
Association and was inducted into the Steel Guitar Hall of Fame in
St. Louis in 1987.
   He also was honored in the Walkway of Stars at the Country Music
Hall of Fame in 1970.
   Drake's distinctive steel guitar style was introduced on such
hits as the 1964 instrumental, ``Forever.''
   As a record producer, Drake worked with Ringo Starr, B.J.
Thomas, Slim Whitman, Boxcar Willie, Melba Montgomery and Ernest
Tubb.
   Drake brought Starr to Nashville to record ``Beaucoups of
Blues'' in 1970, creating a sensation because Starr then became the
first Beatle to record in the United States.
   His instrumental talents were employed by such superstars as Bob
Dylan, George Harrison, Roger Miller, Elvis Presley, Andy Williams,
Kenny Rogers, George Jones, Joan Baez, Tammy Wynette and The Oak
Ridge Boys.
   He started as a road musician and sideman on the Grand Ole Opry,
and later operated several record labels, including Stop Records in
the 1960s and First Generation Records in the 1970s.
   Drake is survived by his wife, Rose Trimble Drake; mother, Nora
Blevins of Nashville; a son and seven daughters; and 13
grandchildren. His funeral is scheduled for Monday afternoon in
Nashville.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
