<HEAD>Boy George, Other Celebrities Tend Store for AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pop music star Boy George peddled clothing and
singer Eartha Kitt ran a hair dryer as about 200 celebrities tended
shop Saturday to raise money for AIDS charities.
   Stars from the music world, theater, television and films
volunteered their services to 251 businesses in Covent Garden, a
central London plaza and shopping complex. The businesses agreed to
donate at least 5 percent of Saturday's till to the charities
fighting the deadly disease.
   Colored balloons decked the roofs, pop musicians performed
non-stop on a courtyard stage, and thousands of shoppers and
star-gazers wandered the streets of the shopping district that once
was London's wholesale flower market.
   Shouting fans besieged Boy George when he turned up at a store
to sell clothes.
   ``I was a window dresser, and I used to have my own shop, so I'm
used to selling things,'' he said.
   Ms. Kitt became a hairdresser for a day and set right to work.
   ``You never know when I'm going to be doing this for a living,''
she joked, waving a hair dryer.
   Other stars contributing to the effort included pop singer Rick
Astley, actresses Greta Scacchi and Geraldine James, and actors
Charles Dance and Colin Firth.
