<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GatorMauling     07-30 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gator Mauling,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trapper Mauled By Injured Alligator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trapper attacked by a 10-foot,
500-pound alligator suffered a mangled arm and a bullet wound in
the leg when officers accidentally shot him as they killed the
animal.
   Lee County sheriff's detective Bill Cameron called the mauling
of Joseph Hays the most terrifying thing he has ever seen.
   ``He screamed, `Help me, help me, oh God, please help me,'''
Cameron said. ``It was screaming like I've never heard before. It
sent chills down my spine.''
   Cameron and three other officers opened fire with handguns,
pumping about 10 bullets into the giant reptile. The gator remained
alive but released its grip on Hays, 22.
   The officers pulled Hays clear of the alligator, then shot eight
more times before the beast was dead.
   ``We weren't taking any chances,'' Cameron said.
   Authorities later learned the alligator had been struck by an
automobile only minutes before it attacked Hays.
   The alligator trapper from Port Charlotte was hospitalized in
serious but stable condition at Lee County Memorial Hospital with
the injured arm and a bullet wound in the right calf.
   He is the most recent victim in a series of violent encounters
between humans and alligators in Southwest Florida _ including the
June death of a 4-year-old girl.
   Friday's deadly drama began shortly after 10 p.m. in a darkened
field in North Fort Myers about a mile from the Caloosahatchee
River.
   Cameron was driving in the area when he saw the alligator lying
beside the road. Fearing that joggers might run up on the gator in
the darkness, Cameron radioed the sheriff's department and waited
for help.
   Deputies contacted the Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish
Commission, who in turn notified a trapper licensed to handle
nuisance alligators.
   Randy Pearson, licensed alligator trapper for the game
commission, and Hays, his assistant, arrived to capture the animal.
The animal attacked when Pearson was sitting astride it, holding
its jaws closed while Hays prepared to tape them shut.
   Game commission Sgt. Ray Hager said injuries probably made the
alligator more aggressive than it normally would have been.
</TEXT>
