<HEAD>Another 10 Arrested; They Won't Identify Themselves, Either</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Chicago ceremony. Picks up
4th graf pvs, `The arrested...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten anti-abortion demonstrators were arrested
Saturday at an Atlanta women's clinic and went to jail refusing to
identify themselves, as more than 100 others have done in the past
two weeks.
   Meanwhile, more than 180 supporters of the Atlanta protest were
arrested in Pittsburgh, but police said most were quickly released.
   In Chicago, two caskets containing what an anti-abortion group
said were 2,000 fetuses were lowered in graves Saturday during a
ceremony officiated at by Roman Catholic Cardinal Joseph Bernardin.
   The Pro-Life Action League, which arranged the burial, said the
fetuses were obtained from clinics and hospitals in five states,
along with the names of the mothers and the physicians who
performed the abortions.
   The Atlanta demonstrators were arrested Saturday morning at the
Atlanta Women's Medical Center after they blocked entrances. Other
protesters urged women not to go in for their abortion appointments.
   The arrested demonstrators, all charged with criminal
trespassing, refused to identify themselves and were held, jail
officials said.
   The demonstration was the latest by ``Operation Rescue,'' which
has staged several protests here since the Democratic National
Convention two weeks ago.
   Many of those arrested have refused to give their names, calling
themselves ``Baby Jane Doe'' or ``Baby John Doe,'' in solidarity,
they say, with aborted fetuses.
   Some demonstrators have been released on their own recognizance,
but officials say they cannot release people who will not give
their names and addresses because they could not be found again for
trial. Most have pleaded innocent to criminal trespass charges.
   Operation Rescue spokesman Lowell Patterson said about 75
percent of the demonstrators have vowed to remain in jail until
their appearances in State Court, if that date is within the next
month or so. Others probably will give their names before that
because of business or personal concerns, he said.
   In Pittsburgh about 180 anti-abortion protesters were arrested
and cited for obstructing traffic during a Saturday morning sit-in
sponsored by Operation Rescue at a building housing two abortion
clinics.
   Most had been released by mid-day, Sgt. Michael Lucia said.
Their citations require them to appear before a judge at a later
date, he said. Police said all gave their names.
   Protesters sang, prayed and listened to speeches, group
spokeswoman Barbara Page said. ``Everyone remained peaceful and
nonviolent,'' but Page said some members complained of hair pulling
and shoving during the arrest.
</TEXT>
