<HEAD>Sharpton, Seeger and Others Jailed for Protest Get Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YVETTE H. BLACKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folk singer Pete Seeger, New York City
activist Al Sharpton and 10 others were released Saturday night
after spending one day in jail for disorderly conduct in a racially
charged protest over an alleged rape.
   Attorney Alton Maddox Jr., representing Sharpton and 10 others,
refused to call the release a victory.
   ``In a case that did not measure up to a criminal conviction,''
Maddox said he was surprised at Albany Police Court Judge Thomas
Keegan's decision ``to put everybody away immediately.''
   ``It caused some hardships,'' Maddox said. ``There was no gap
between conviction and sentence.''
   Seeger's lawyer, William A. Brenner, showed up at the Albany
jail with Seeger's banjo.
   ``Pete Seeger doesn't understand all this legal mumbo-jumbo,''
Brenner said. ``When he sees a banjo, he knows he's out.''
   ``I wanted to express my unity with people I considered my
brothers and sisters,'' Seeger said outside the jail. ``I am very
happy to have done so.''
   As the group left the jail about 10:35 p.m, Sharpton called out
to guards, ``I'll be back but I might be late for basketball
tomorrow.''
   Sharpton, appearing to be in high spirits, said he attended
church services Saturday morning and played basketball with some of
the inmates. The rotund minister said he spent the day fasting and
had lost about 2 pounds.
   The six men and six women were ordered released, pending an
appeal, by New York State Supreme Court Judge Paul Cheeseman, who
met at his home for three hours with Maddox, Brenner, Albany County
District Attorney Sol Greenberg and attorney C. Vernon Mason.
   Mason, Maddox and Sharpton have been acting as advisers for
Tawana Brawley, a black Wappingers Falls teen-ager who claims she
was abducted and sexually assaulted by six white men last November.
   Sharpton, Seeger and 10 others were found guilty Friday of
blocking traffic in downtown Albany during an April 4 demonstration
on behalf of Ms. Brawley. Brawley family members have refused to
cooperate with investigators and have claimed they cannot get
justice because of official racism.
   The protesters were sentenced to 15 days in jail. Two other
defendants were acquitted after a three-day, non-jury trial heard
by Keegan.
</TEXT>
