<HEAD>328 Lift and Move Barn Near Bruno</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Add a graf with reason for moving barn.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto CNB1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUNO, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Still energetic after 100 years, this town
helped a farmer relocate his barn by picking it up and moving it
about 110 feet.
   At Bruno's centennial celebration Saturday, 328 volunteers
grabbed steel poles that Herman Ostry and his sons had placed
underneath their barn. As several hundred spectators cheered, the
volunteers lifted the 60-year-old structure, moved it several feet
and set it down. And they repeated the feat for 20 minutes until
the barn was 10 feet to the east and 100 feet to the north.
   Ostry estimated that the barn weighs nearly nine tons, so each
volunteer had to lift more than 50 pounds, he said.
   After moving the barn to its new home, the volunteers turned the
structure clockwise until the side that was facing west faced the
south.
   Ostrey said he wanted to move the barn to higher, drier ground
and ``to do something different for the centennial, and to make
history.''
</TEXT>
