<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-US     07-30 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-US,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China says U.S. Senate action harms relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Senate measure calling on China to halt
missile sales to the Middle East ``brings harm to Sino-U.S.
relations,'' the Foreign Ministry said Saturday.
   The official Xinhua news agency carried the ministry statement.
   It was in response to an amendment, proposed by Sen. Robert
Dole, R-Kan., and added to a State Department appropriations bill
that was approved Wednesday by a vote of 97-0. The amendment
declares that China should halt its sale of ballistic missiles and
other offensive weapons to nations in the Persian Gulf area and
Middle East immediately.
   It also suggests the United States reassess its relations with
China if the arms sales are not stopped.
   The Foreign Ministry statement said: ``China has always taken a
prudent and responsible attitude toward arms sales. This amendment,
which makes a big fuss about the so-called question of `arms
sales,' brings harm to Sino-U.S. Relations. The Chinese government
is firmly opposed to it.''
   U.S. officials have expressed concern about the sale of Chinese
missiles to Saudi Arabia and reported negotiations with Syria to
sell short-range missiles now being developed. China has denied
plans to sell missiles to Syria.
   Last year, U.S.-Chinese relations were strained by U.S.
allegations that China had sold Silkworm anti-ship missiles to
Iran. China denied the claim.
   The United States last fall temporarily froze a further
relaxation of regulations on high technology sales to China to
protest the alleged arms sales to Iran.
</TEXT>
