<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BoatPeople     07-30 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boat People,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Opens New Detention Center for Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government opened another detention center
for Vietnamese boat people Saturday under a new policy designed to
stem the flow of refugees to this British colony.
   Despite the new policy's aim, more than 6,700 boat people have
sailed into Hong Kong since it went into effect June 15.
   About 1,200 refugees were moved Saturday from ferries moored in
the colony's harbor to Erskine Camp, the third temporary detention
center for the boat people.
   The new policy provides that the Vietnamese be kept in those
centers until Vietnam agrees to take them back.
   Boat people who arrived before the new policy took effect are
still eligible for resettlement. They are kept in refugee centers
separate from the detention centers for recent arrivals.
   All boat people arriving after June 15 are considered illegal
immigrants subject to repatriation unless they can prove they fled
persecution in communist Vietnam. The Hong Kong government
previously considered all boat people refugees eligible for
resettlement.
   More than 16,000 Vietnamese refugees are in Hong Kong.
   Also Saturday, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Ghafar Baba said
he will go to Hanoi next month to discuss the refugee issue with
Vietnamese leaders. Ghafar did not say when his delegation would
leave for Vietnam, according to Malaysia's Bernama news agency.
   It quoted him as saying about 13,000 Vietnamese refugees are in
Malaysia awaiting resettlement in other countries.
</TEXT>
